INSERT INTO `codename` VALUES (1,'ALTEREGO QFD','alterego-qfd','A [question focused dataset](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Question-focused_dataset) for social media selectors.','Very little is known about ALTEREGO QFD. It is a system used for finding selectors, such as usernames, cookies, IP addresses, etc. Selectors are used for targeting with [QUANTUM](/quantumtheory).','2015-01-15 04:08:44','2015-12-09 04:58:44'),(2,'ANGRYNEIGHBOR','angryneighbor','A family of RF retro reflector bugs.','This family of bugs, including [CTX4000](/ctx4000), [PHOTOANGLO](/photoanglo),  [SURLYSPAWN](/surlyspawn), and [TAWDRYYARD](/tawdryyard), is designed to surveil electronic equipment like fax machines, printers, keyboards, mice, etc. These stealthy bugs do not emit radiation unless actively illuminated and can be monitored remotely. Some of the implants are incredibly tiny, measuring less than 1/4\" across.','2015-01-15 04:09:00','2015-07-15 05:10:11'),(3,'ANTO LP PROTOSS GUI','anto-lp-protoss-gui','Control software used by the [ROC](/roc) for managing software implants.','Not much is known about ANTO LP PROTOSS GUI. The ROC apparently uses this software for managing and re-deploying software implants. Its existence was revealed in the [ANT implant catalog](http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/NSA_ANT_catalog) entry for [IRONCHEF](/ironchef).','2015-01-15 04:27:44','2015-12-08 22:59:56'),(4,'ARKSTREAM','arkstream','A [BIOS](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/BIOS) flashing utility.','Used to deploy BIOS implants such as [DEITYBOUNCE](/deitybounce) or [SWAP](/swap).','2015-01-15 04:27:50','2015-12-08 22:13:54'),(5,'ARTEMIS','artemis','A direction finding system for radio frequency (RF) signals.','Little is known about ARTEMIS. It is mentioned in the [ANT implant catalog](http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/NSA_ANT_catalog) entry for [ENTOURAGE](/entourage). It is apparently some sort of direction finding system for wireless signals that was made obsolete by ENTOURAGE.','2015-01-15 04:27:57','2015-12-08 23:09:34'),(6,'BACONRIDGE','baconridge','A covert facility in San Antonio, TX that houses the majority of the [TAO](/tao) workforce.','This 42,000 sq. ft. facility contains work space for TAO\'s 270 employees, including 210 workstations, a training lab, a \"Technical Demonstration Center\",  multiple conference/activity rooms, 200 server racks, and 9,450 sq. ft. of data center floor space.','2015-01-15 04:28:01','2015-12-08 23:21:38'),(7,'BANANAGLEE','bananaglee','A software implant from the [ANT implant catalog](http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/NSA_ANT_catalog) that targets routers.','This software implant runs on a variety of routers from Juniper and Cisco. The exact capabilities of BANANAGLEE are unknown. Presumably, it enables remote management of the router as well as data exfiltration.\n\nBANANAGLEE is persisted using a firmware implant such as [FEEDTROUGH](/feedtrough), [GOURMETTROUGH](/gourmettrough), or [SOUFFLETROUGH](/souffletrough). It is similar to [ZESTYLEAK](/zestyleak).','2015-01-15 04:28:08','2015-12-09 00:13:03'),(10,'BLACKHEART','blackheart','A [SIGAD](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/SIGINT_Activity_Designator) that designates signals collected from an FBI implant.','Not much is known about this SIGAD.','2015-01-15 04:28:44','2015-12-09 00:42:27'),(11,'BLACKPEARL','blackpearl','A database of routing metadata about the internet.','The database holds [5-tuples](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Tuple) of routing data about \"identified routers, routing protocols, [and] SIGINT access points.\"','2015-01-15 04:28:53','2015-07-25 18:47:54'),(12,'BLINDDATE','blinddate','A suite of software tools for performing wireless network reconnaissance.','This software runs on the [SPARROW II](/sparow-ii) hardware.','2015-01-15 04:29:01','2015-07-24 06:13:33'),(14,'BULLDOZER','bulldozer','A hardware implant from the  [ANT implant catalog](http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/NSA_ANT_catalog) that runs the [GINSU](/ginsu) persistence implant for [KONGUR](/kongur).','Infosec Institute speculates that BULLDOZER is a PCI expansion card containing an option ROM, possibly masquerading as a wireless networking card. The GINSU \"concept of operations\" diagram suggests that a single device implanted with BULLDOZER can be used to implant KONGUR on other nearby devices.','2015-01-15 04:29:51','2015-07-18 03:16:30'),(15,'Byzantine Anchor','byzantine-anchor','A subprogram within [Byzantine Hades](/byzantine-hades).','Little is known about this program.','2015-01-15 04:30:06','2015-12-09 01:52:30'),(16,'Byzantine Candor','byzantine-candor','A subprogram within [Byzantine Hades](/byzantine-hades).','Little is known about this program.','2015-01-15 04:30:13','2015-12-09 01:52:32'),(17,'Byzantine Hades','byzantine-hades','A program to combat Chinese hackers.','Little is known about this program.','2015-01-15 04:30:21','2015-07-25 19:34:13'),(18,'CANDYGRAM','candygram','An implant from the [ANT implant catalog](http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/NSA_ANT_catalog) that acts like a virtual tripwire device by imitating a [GSM](http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/GSM) cellular phone tower.','Mimics GSM cell tower of a target network. Capable of operations at 900, 1800, or 1900 MHz. Whenever a target handset enters the CANDYGRAM base station\'s area of influence, the system sends out an SMS through the external network to registered watch phones.\n\nTypical use scenarios are asset validation, target tracking and identification as well as identifying hostile surveillance units with GSM handsets. Functionality is predicated on a priori target information.\n\n#### System HW\n\n* GPS processing unit\n* Tri-band BTS radio\n* Windows XP laptop and cell phone*\n* 9\" wide x 12\" long x 2\" deep\n* External power (9-30 VDC).\n\n\\*Remote control software can be used with any connected to the laptop (used for communicating with the CANDYGRAM unit through text messages (SMS).\n\n#### SW Features\n\n* Configurable 200 phone number target deck.\n* Network auto-configuration\n* Area Survey Capability\n* Remote Operation Capability\n* Configurable Network emulation\n* Configurable RF power level\n* Multi-Units under single C&C\n* Remote restart\n* Remote erasure (not field recoverable)\n\n*Unit Cost*: $40,000','2015-01-15 04:30:40','2015-12-09 05:46:51'),(19,'CDR Diode','cdr-diode','Common Data Receptor','Not a codename but an acronym. A CDR appears to be a low-to-high [data diode](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Unidirectional_network), meaning that it allows captured traffic from the internet to be moved into the agency\'s classified network for storage and analysis.','2015-01-15 04:30:50','2015-07-25 15:05:39'),(20,'CHIMNEYPOOL','chimneypool','A framework for remotely controlling software implants.','This framework provides technologies for remotely controlling software implants, in particular sending commands to them and receiving information back from them.\n\nCHIMNEYPOOL uses a proprietary [remote procedure call (RPC)](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Remote_procedure_call) system on top of a [FRIEZERAMP](/friezeramp) network stack. Nodes may be connected to each other via [half-duplex](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Duplex_(telecommunications)#HALF-DUPLEX) links. Links can be encrypted or unencrypted.\n\nThe system can communicate with the [NCC](/ncc) if it has been deployed with the correct encryption keys.\n\nThe system can also communicate with [TURBINE](/turbine) using [SURPLUSHANGAR](/surplushangar) and [HANGARSURPLUS](/hangarsurplus) data diodes.','2015-01-15 04:30:58','2015-07-24 05:28:17'),(21,'COMMONDEER','commondeer','A \"stage 1\" software implant deployed by [QUANTUMTHEORY](/quantumtheory).','This implant is the successor to [VALIDATOR](/validator) and is used in the QUANTUM framework to install a permanent backdoor on a targeted system. As a stage 1 implant, it is used to install other software implants but contains no surveillance capability itself.','2015-01-15 04:31:23','2016-01-04 05:34:27'),(22,'CONJECTURE','conjecture','A radio frequency (RF) communications protocol used by [HOWLERMONKEY](/howlermonkey).','Little is known about this communications protocol.','2015-01-15 04:31:27','2015-12-09 02:23:22'),(23,'COTTONMOUTH-I','cottonmouth-i','A USB implant from the [ANT implant catalog](http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/NSA_ANT_catalog) disguised as a [USB type A cable](http://pcsupport.about.com/od/termsu/a/usb-type-a.htm) that creates a wireless bridge into a target network as well as the ability to load exploit software onto target PCs.','COTTONMOUTH-I (CM-I) is a Universal Serial Bus (USB) hardware implant which will provide a wireless bridge into a target network as well as the ability to load exploit software onto target PCs.\n\nCM-I provides air-gap bridging, software persistence capability, \"in-field\" re-programmability, and covert communications with a host software implant over the USB. The RF link will enable command and data infiltration and exfiltration. CM-I will also communicate with Data Network Technologies (DNT) software ([STRAITBIZARRE](/straitbizarre)) through a covert channel implemented on the USB, using this communication channel to pass commands and data between hardware and software implants. CM-I will be a GENIE-compliant implant based on [CHIMNEYPOOL](/chimneypool).\n\nCM-I conceals digital components ([TRINITY](/trinity)), USB 1.1 FS hub, switches, and [HOWLERMONKEY (HM)](/howlermonkey) RF Transceiver within the USB Series-A cable connector. [MOCCASIN](/moccasin) is the version permanently connected to a USB keyboard. Another version can be made with an unmodified USB connector at the other end. CM-I has the ability to communicate to other CM devices over the RF link using an over-the-air protocol called [SPECULATION](/speculation).\n\n*Unit Cost:* $20,300 (minimum order 50 units)','2015-01-15 04:31:47','2015-12-09 15:24:53'),(24,'COTTONMOUTH-II','cottonmouth-ii','A USB implant from the [ANT implant catalog](http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/NSA_ANT_catalog) disguised as a stacked USB Type-A connector (http://pcsupport.about.com/od/termsu/a/usb-type-a.htm) that creates a wireless bridge into a target network as well as the ability to load exploit software onto target PCs.','COTTONMOUTH-II (CM-II) is a Universal Serial Bus (USB) hardware Host Tap, which will provide a covert link over USB link into a target network. CM-II is intended to be operate with a long haul relay subsystem, which is co-located within the target equipment. Further integration is needed to turn this capability into a deployable system.\n\nCM-II will provide software persistence capability, \"in-field\" re-programmability, and covert communications with a host software implant over the USB. CM-II will also communicate with Data Network Technologies (DNT) software ([STRAITBIZARRE](/straitbizarre)) through a covert channel implemented on the USB, using this communication channel to pass commands and data between hardware and software implants. CM-II will be a GENIE-compliant implant based on [CHIMNEYPOOL](/chimneypool).\n\nCM-II consists of the CM-I digital hardware and the long haul relay concealed somewhere within the target chassis. A USB 2.0 HS hub with switches is concealed in a dual stacked USB connector, and the two parts are hard-wired, providing a intra-chassis link. The long haul relay provides the wireless bridge into the target\'s network.\n\n*Unit Cost:* $40,000 (minimum order 50 units)','2015-01-15 04:31:53','2015-12-09 15:25:07'),(25,'COTTONMOUTH-III','cottonmouth-iii','A USB implant from the [ANT implant catalog](http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/NSA_ANT_catalog) disguised as a stacked Type-A USB/RJ45 connector that creates a wireless bridge into a target network as well as the ability to load exploit software onto target PCs.','COTTONMOUTH-III provides air-gap bridging, software persistence capability, \"in-field\" re-programmability, and covert communications with a host software implant over USB. The RF link will enable command and data infiltration and exfiltration. CM-III will also communicate with [Data Network Technologies (DNT)](/dnt) software ([STRAITBIZARRE](/straitbizarre)) through a covert channel implemented on the USB, using this communication channel to pass commands and data between hardware and software implants. CM-III will be a [GENIE-compliant](/genie) implant based on [CHIMNEYPOOL](/chimneypool).\n\nCOTTONMOUTH-III conceals digital components ([TRINITY](/trinity)), USB 2.0 HS hub, switches, and [HOWLERMONKEY (HM)](/howlermonkey) RF Transceiver within a RJ45 Dual Stacked USB connector. CM-I has the ability to communicate to other CM devices over the RF link using an over-the-air protocol called [SPECULATION](/speculation). CM-III can provide a short range inter-chassis link to other CM devices or an intra-chassis RF link to a long haul relay subsystem.\n\n*Unit Cost:* $24,960 (minimum order 50 units)','2015-01-15 04:32:00','2015-12-09 15:25:30'),(26,'CROSSBEAM','crossbeam','CROSSBEAM is a [GSM](http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/GSM) module from the [ANT implant catalog](http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/NSA_ANT_catalog) that mates a modified commercial cellular product with a [WAGONBED](/wagonbed) controller board.','CROSSBEAM is a reusable [CHIMNEYPOOL-compliant](/chimneypool) GSM communications module capable of collecting and compressing voice data. CROSSBEAM can receive GSM voice, record voice data, and transmit the received information via connected modules or 4 different GSM data modes ([GPRS](http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/General_Packet_Radio_Service), Circuit Switched Data, Data Over Voice, and [DTMF](http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Dual-tone_multi-frequency_signaling)) back to a secure facility. The CROSSBEAM module consists of a standard ANT architecture embedded computer, a specialized phone component, a customized software controller suite and an optional DSP ([ROCKYKNOB](/rockyknob)) of using Data Over Voice to transmit data.\n\n*Unit Cost:* $4,000','2015-01-15 04:32:06','2015-01-17 05:52:02'),(27,'CRUMPET Covert Network','crumpet-covert-network','An implant system that is used to exfiltrate data from air gapped networks.','A CRUMPET Covert Network is a data exfiltration system that relies on installing hardware implants (via supply chain interdiction) onto devices that are installed on air gapped networks.\n\nInstead of installing the implant directly on a computer or server to be monitored, the implant is installed on a nearby device, including printer, computer, or server. The CRUMPET implants can communicate with other hosts via [IRONCHEF](/ironchef). \n\nThis elaborate set up allows, for example, air gapped nodes running [STRAITBIZARRE] to exfiltrate data to an implanted device elsewhere on the network. That device, in turn, can exfiltrate data over [GSM](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/GSM) or other radio frequency protocols.','2015-01-15 04:32:43','2015-12-09 02:20:31'),(28,'CRYPTO ENABLED','crypto-enabled','A [SIGAD](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/SIGINT_Activity_Designator) that designates signals collected from \"AO\'s efforts to enable crypto.\"','Little is known about this SIGAD.','2015-01-15 04:32:55','2015-12-09 02:26:45'),(29,'CTX4000','ctx4000','CTX4000 is a radar unit from the [ANT implant catalog](http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/NSA_ANT_catalog) that is used to illuminate passive implants.','The CTX4000 is a portable continuous wave (CW) radar unit. It can be used to illuminate a target system to recover different off net information. Radar illumination is used to gather data from passive implants that do not otherwise produce strong radio frequency signals; the system behaves in a manner similar to [RFID](http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Radio-frequency_identification). Primary uses include [VAGRANT](/vagrant) and [DROPMIRE](/dropmire) collection.\n\nThe CTX4000 provides the means to collect signals that otherwise would not be collectable, or would be extremely difficult to collect and process. It provides the following features:\n\n* Frequency Range: 1 - 2 GHz.\n* Bandwidth: Up to 45 MHz\n* Output Power: User adjustable up to 2 W using the internal amplifier; external amplifiers make it possible to go up to 1 kW.\n* Phase adjustment with front panel knob\n* User-selectable high- and low-pass filters.\n* Remote controllable\n* Outputs:\n  * Transmit antenna\n  * I and Q video outputs\n  * DC bias for an external pre-amp on the Receive input connector\n* Inputs:\n  * External oscillator\n  * Receive antenna\n\n*Unit Cost:* N/A','2015-01-15 04:33:03','2015-01-18 04:22:20'),(30,'CUSTOMS','customs','A [SIGAD](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/SIGINT_Activity_Designator) that designates data collected from customs interdiction (i.e. border crossings).','This SIGAD designates data collected from seizing (either temporarily or indefinitely) electronic devices from travelers going through customs, i.e. a border crossing. These electronic devices can be imaged in order to analyze data later, or they may be implanted with hardware or software to allow continuing monitoring and collection of data.','2015-01-15 04:33:17','2015-12-09 01:48:30'),(31,'CYCLONE Hx9','cyclone-hx9','CYCLONE Hx9 is a \"network-in-a-box\" from the [ANT implant catalog](http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/NSA_ANT_catalog) that is used for setting up a cellular phone network.','CYCLONE Hx9 is an EGSM (900MGz) macro-class Network-In-a-Box (NIB) system. It uses the existing [Typhon GUI](/typhon) and supports the full Typhon feature base and applications.\n\n#### Features\n\n* EGSM 900MHz\n* Macro-class (+43dBm)\n* 32+Km Range\n* Optional Battery Kits\n* Highly Mobile and Deployable\n* Integrated GPS, MS, & 802.11\n* Voice & High-speed Data\n* GSM Security & Encryption\n\n#### Advanced Features\n\n* GPS -- Supporting Typhon applications\n* GSM Handset Module -- Supports auto-configuration and remote command and control features.\n* 802.11 -- Supports high speed wireless LAN remote command and control\n\n#### Enclosure\n\n* 3.5\"H x 8.5\"W x 9\"D\n* Approximately 8 lbs\n* Actively cooled for extreme environments\n\n#### Cyclone Hx9 System Kit\n\n* Cyclone Hx9 System\n* AC/DC power converter\n* Antenna to support MS, GPS, WIFI, & RF\n* LAN, RF, & USB cables\n* Pelican Case\n* (Field Kit only) Control Laptop and Accessories\n\n#### Separately Priced Options\n\n* 800 WH LiIon Battery Kit\n\n#### Base Station Router Platform\n\n* Overlay GSM cellular communications supporting up to 32 Cyclone Mx9 systems providing full mobility and utilizing a VoIP back-haul.\n* GPRS data service and associated application\n\n*Unit Cost:* $70,000 for two months','2015-01-15 04:33:35','2015-01-18 03:45:02'),(32,'DANDERSPRITZ','danderspritz','A tool for creating a \"redirector node\", i.e. a network node for tunneling traffic from implants back to the [ROC](/roc).','This tool can be used to create a VPN endpoint for receiving exfiltrated data from an implant like [FIREWALK](/firewalk). This endpoint redirects traffic to a ROC endpoint, masking the ROC endpoint\'s MAC/IP address.','2015-01-15 04:33:47','2015-12-09 02:33:00'),(33,'DARKTHUNDER','darkthunder','A [SIGAD](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/SIGINT_Activity_Designator) that designates signals collected from [TAO](/tao).','Little is known about this SIGAD.','2015-01-15 04:33:53','2015-12-09 02:41:54'),(34,'DEWSWEEPER','dewsweeper','A USB hardware \"host tap\" that provides a covert wireless bridge into a target network.','Little is known about this implant.','2015-01-15 04:34:00','2015-12-09 01:38:55'),(35,'DEITYBOUNCE','deitybounce','A software implant from the [ANT implant catalog](http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/NSA_ANT_catalog) that provides backdoor access to Dell PowerEdge servers.','The implant uses the BIOS and the CPU\'s [System Management Mode (SMM)](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/System_Management_Mode) to periodically execute code while the operating system loads.\n\nIt supports Windows 2000, 2003, and XP. It targets Dell PowerEdge 1850, 2850, 1950, and 2950 servers using BIOS versions A02, A04, A06, 1.1.0, 1.2.0, or 1.3.7. Curiously, the implant requires the presence of a RAID controller. (Compare to the similar [IRATEMONK](/iratemonk) implant that modifies hard drive firmware.)\n\nDEITYBOUNCE is implanted by [ARKSTREAM](/arkstream) using either a remote access exploit or supply chain interdiction. Supply chain interdiction is can be performed by a non-technical operator with just a USB thumb drive.\n\nThe implant does not appear to contain any surveillance functionality itself; it is apparently intended to provide stealth and persistence for other implants.\n\n*Unit Cost:* $0','2015-01-15 04:34:22','2015-07-21 03:12:59'),(36,'DOCKETDICTATE','docketdictate','An unknown tool within [TAO](/tao).','The only known mention of this tool is in a brief on the Texas Cryptologic Center (a.k.a. [BACONRIDGE](/baconridge)). This tool was designated for installation in November 2008 in room 137 at BACONRIDGE.','2015-01-15 04:34:30','2015-12-09 02:54:59'),(37,'DOGCOLLAR QFD','dogcollar-qfd','A [question focused dataset](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Question-focused_dataset) for social media selectors.','Very little is known about DOGCOLLAR QFD. It is a system used for finding selectors, such as usernames, cookies, IP addresses, etc. Selectors are used for targeting with [QUANTUM](/quantumtheory).','2015-01-15 04:34:37','2015-12-09 04:58:52'),(38,'DROPMIRE','dropmire','A surveillance tool that collects signals from radio frequency emanations of fax machines and printers.','This tool allows passive surveillance of a fax machine or laser printer from a nearby location. \n\nThis tool was notably used to spy on diplomats at the EU Embassy in Washington, DC in 2007. In that case, the tool was used to monitor faxes sent using a [Cryptofax](http://mar747.en.ec21.com/Cryptofax_3000_facsimile_encryption_equipment--408079_843459.html) machine — a machine that encrypts fax communications. The encryption used by the device was not attacked directly; instead, hazy (but readable) copies of the fax machine\'s print outs were produced by monitoring the fax machine\'s RF emanations.','2015-01-15 04:34:45','2015-12-09 01:14:44'),(39,'DROPOUT JEEP','dropout-jeep','A software implant from the [ANT implant catalog](http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/NSA_ANT_catalog) that targets Apple iOS devices and uses the [CHIMNEYPOOL](/chimneypool) framework.','This software implant is based on the CHINEYPOOL framework, is compliant with the [FREEFLOW](/freeflow) project and is supported in the [TURBULENCE](/turbulence) architecture. It provides the following surveillance capabilities:\n\n* Push or pull files from the device.\n* Read [SMS](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Short_Message_Service) messages off of the device.\n* Copy contact list off of the device.\n* Listen to target\'s voicemail.\n* Geolocate the target device.\n* Record audio from the device\'s microphone.\n* Take pictures or video using the device\'s camera.\n* Identify which cell towers the device is communicating with.\n\nAll of these capabilities can be remotely controlled by SMS messaging or [GPRS](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/General_Packet_Radio_Service) data.\n\nAll of these communications are encrypted and transmitted on a covert channel. The NSA claims that this implant has a 100% success rate when it comes to installation.\n\nThe implant is installed via \"close access methods\", but remote installation capability is being pursued for a future release.\n\n*Unit Cost:* $0','2015-01-15 04:34:52','2015-07-21 03:30:04'),(40,'DRTBOX','drtbox','A wireless surveillance product sold by [Digital Receiver Technology, Inc.](http://www.drti.com/) that emulates a cellular base station.','This is not an NSA codename, per se. This is simply how NSA analysts refer to this commercial device. The device is also used by other U.S. agencies as well as other governments.','2015-01-15 04:35:07','2015-12-09 03:29:12'),(41,'EBSR','ebsr','EBSR is a GSM base station from the [ANT implant catalog](http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/NSA_ANT_catalog) that can be used for setting up a cellular network.','EBSR is a multi-purpose, Pico class, tri-band active GSM base station with internal 802.11/GPS/handset capability.\n\n#### Features\n\n* LxT Model: 900/1800/1900MHz\n* LxU Model: 850/1800/1900MHz\n* Pico-class (1Watt) Base station\n* Optional Battery Kits\n* Highly Mobile and Deployable\n* Integrated GPS, MS, & 802.11\n* Voice & High-speed Data\n* SMS Capability\n\n#### Enclosure\n\n* 1.9\"H x 8.6\"W x 6.3\"D\n* Approximately 3 lbs\n* Actively cooled for extreme environments\n\n#### EBSR System Kit\n\n* EBSR System\n* AC/DC power converter\n* Antenna to support MS, GPS, WIFI, & RF\n* LAN, RF, & USB cables\n* Pelican Case\n* (Field Kit only) Control Laptop and Accessories\n\n#### Separately Priced Options\n\n* 90 WH LiIon Battery Kit\n\n#### Base Station Router Platform\n\n* Multiple BSR units can be interconnected to form a macro network using 802.3 and 802.11 back-haul.\n* Supports Landshark/Candygram capabilities.\n\nUnit Cost: $40,000','2015-01-15 04:35:17','2015-01-17 05:08:40'),(42,'EGOTISTICALGIRAFFE','egotisticalgiraffe','A system for fingerprinting and exploiting [Tor](https://www.torproject.org/) users.','This program includes several exploits, such as [ERRONEOUSINGENUITY](/erroneousingenuity) and [EGOTISTICALGOAT](/egotisticalgoat) that allow exploitation of Tor users using vulnerable versions of the Tor Browser Bundle.','2015-01-15 04:36:04','2015-12-09 03:39:39'),(43,'EGOTISTICALGOAT','egotisticalgoat','An exploit for Firefox versions 11.9-16.0.2.','Also known as \"EGGO\", this exploit was used against [Tor](https://www.torproject.org/) users under the [EGOTISTICALGIRAFFE](/egotisticalgiraffe) program. It exploits a type confusion vulnerability in [ECMAScript for XML](https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Archive/Web/E4X), enabling arbitrary read/write to system memory as well as code execution.','2015-01-15 04:36:10','2015-12-09 03:38:34'),(44,'ENTOURAGE','entourage','A direction finder from the [ANT implant catalog](http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/NSA_ANT_catalog) used for locating the source of cellular phone radio transmissions.','ENTOURAGE is a component of the [HOLLOWPOINT](/hollowpoint) platform. The system is capable of providing line of bearing for [GSM](http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/GSM), [UMTS](http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Universal_Mobile_Telecommunications_System), [CDMA2000](http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Code_division_multiple_access), and [FRS](http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Family_Radio_Service) signals. A band-specific antenna and laptop controller is needed to compliment the HOLLOWPOINT system and completes the ground based system.\n\nThe ENTOURAGE application leverages the 4 Software Defined Radio (SDR) units in the HOLLOWPOINT platform. This capability provides an \"Artemis-like\" capability for waveforms of interest (2G, 3G, and others). The ENTOURAGE application works in conjunction with the [NEBULA](/nebula) active interrogator as part of the [Find/Fix/Finish](/find-fix-finish) capabilities of the [GALAXY](/galaxy) program.\n\n#### Features\n\n* Software Defined Radio System\n* Operating range 10MHz - 4GHz\n* 4 Receive paths, all synchronized\n* 1 Transmit path\n* DF capability on GSM/UMTS/CDMA2000/FRS signals\n* Gigabit Ethernet\n* Integrated GPS\n* Highly Mobile and Deployable\n\n#### Specifications\n\n* 1.8\"H x 8.0\"W x 8.0\"D\n* Approximately 3 lbs\n* 15 Watts\n* Passively cooled\n\n#### Future Developments:\n\n* WiMAX\n* WiFi\n* LTE\n\n*Unit Cost*: $70,000','2015-01-15 04:36:17','2015-12-09 05:19:05'),(47,'FAIRVIEW','fairview','A corporate collections program in the [TURMOIL](/turmoil) project.','Not much is known about this collections program.\n\n[Domain Awareness](https://twitter.com/domainawareness) posted purported FAIRVIEW slides on Twitter. The slides indicate that the unnamed partner is based in the USA, grabbing signals off of cables, switches, and routers. The partner also provides access to outside data through some of their corporate relationships. The slide states that only \"domestic infrastructure\" is included in the program, but also indicates access to trans-Pacific and trans-Atlantic international data. The program operates under multiple authorities, including Transit, FISA, and FAA and collects both content and metadata. Domain Awareness claims that the unnamed parter is AT&T.','2015-01-15 04:36:43','2016-02-04 17:09:05'),(48,'FEEDTROUGH','feedtrough','A persistence implant from the [ANT implant catalog](http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/NSA_ANT_catalog) that targets Juniper firewalls: ns5xt, ns25, ns50, ns200, ns500, and isg1000.','FEEDTROUGH is a persistence technique for two software implants, DNT\'s [BANANAGLEE](/bananaglee) and CES\'s [ZESTYLEAK](/zestyleak) used against Juniper Netscreen firewalls.\n\nFEEDTROUGH can be used to persist two implants, ZESTYLEAK and/or BANANAGLEE across reboots and software upgrades on known and covered OS\'s for the following Netscreen firewalls, ns5xt, ns25, ns50, ns200, ns500 and ISG 1000. There is no direct communication to or from FEEDTROUGH, but if present, the BANANAGLEE implant can receive and transmit covert channel comms, and for certain platforms, BANANAGLEE can also update FEEDTROUGH. FEEDTROUGH however can only persist OS\'s included in its databases. Therefore this is best employed with known OS\'s and if a new OS comes out, then the customer would need to add this OS to the FEEDTROUGH database for that particular firewall.\n\nFEEDTROUGH operates every time the particular Juniper firewall boots. The first hook takes it to the code which checks to see if the OS is in the database, if it is, then a chain of events ensures the installation of either one or both implants. Otherwise the firewall boots normally. If the OS is one modified by DNT, it is not recognized, which gives the customer freedom to field new software.\n\n*Unit Cost:* $0','2015-01-15 04:36:50','2015-12-09 04:48:02'),(49,'FERRETCANNON','ferretcannon','An exploit delivery system used within [FOXACID](/foxacid).','This system has been mentioned in the press but the original source document that contains it has never been published, so few details are available.','2015-01-15 04:36:55','2015-12-09 04:00:53'),(50,'FINKDIFFERENT','finkdifferent','A protocol for software exploits to call back to [C&C](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Command_and_control_(malware)) servers.','Little is known about this protocol. It\'s only mention comes in a presentation about [EGOTISTICALGIRAFFE](/egotisticalgiraffe), but the implication is that it used for exploits to call back to C&C servers. This particular callback does not work in Tor.','2015-01-15 04:37:08','2015-12-09 04:07:27'),(51,'FIREWALK','firewalk','A tiny implant (~1 cubic inch) from the [ANT implant catalog](http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/NSA_ANT_catalog) used for eavesdropping on and injecting traffic into ethernet networks using a radio signal. It effectively creates a wireless bridge into an otherwise air-gapped network. ','FIREWALK is a bi-directional network implant, capable of passively collecting 10/100/1000BT Ethernet network traffic, and actively injecting Ethernet packets onto the same target network. The implant resides within a dual stacked RJ45 / USB connector. \n\nIt is capable of filtering and egressing network traffic over a custom RF link and injecting traffic as commanded; this allows a ethernet tunnel (VPN) to be created between target network and the remote operator\'s console (or an intermediate redirector node such as DNT\'s [DANDERSPRITZ](/danderspritz) tool.) FIREWALK allows active exploitation of a target network with a firewall or air gap protection.\n\nFIREWALK uses the [HOWLERMONKEY](/howlermonkey) transceiver for back-end communications. It can communicate with an LP or other compatible HOWLERMONKEY based ANT products to increase RF range through multiple hops.\n\n*Unit Cost:* $10,740 (minimum order 50 units )','2015-01-15 04:37:16','2015-12-09 20:57:04'),(52,'FLUXBABBIT','fluxbabbit','A hardware implant from the [ANT implant catalog](http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/NSA_ANT_catalog) that targets Dell PowerEdge 1950 and 2950 servers.','This hardware implant attaches to the [JTAG](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Joint_Test_Action_Group) port on a Dell server\'s motherboard. The server must be intercepted via supply chain interdiction, then a JTAG port must be soldered onto the motherboard. Finally, the hardware implant can be slotted into the JTAG port.\n\nThe implant is preloaded with a software implant called [GODSURGE](/godsurge). This tandem of hardware and software provides persistence for a surveillance software implant.','2015-01-15 04:37:25','2015-12-09 04:18:42'),(54,'FOXACID','foxacid','A [man-on-the-side](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Man-on-the-side_attack) exploitation system.','When a targeted user contacts a legitimate website, FOXACID sends a response that races to the user before the legitimate website has had a chance to respond. The response appears to come from the legitimate website but is implanted with a FOXACID URL (presumably via [iframe](http://www.w3schools.com/tags/tag_iframe.asp) or some other technical means).\n\nOnce the user\'s computer makes contact with FOXACID, the system can select a suitable exploit for that user, presumably based on browser and OS fingerprinting, and deliver a stage 1 exploit. If the stage 1 exploit is successful, it can load additional stages from the FOXACID server.','2015-01-15 04:37:35','2015-07-25 20:15:29'),(55,'FOXSEARCH','foxsearch','A management application for [FOXACID](/foxacid) tasking.','An analyst using FOXACID must obtain a Twisty Lobby Number (TLN) in order to create tasking for FOXACID. After submitting the task, the analyst can monitor the results with the FOXSEARCH tool.','2015-01-15 04:37:40','2015-12-09 04:24:17'),(56,'FREEFLOW','freeflow','A high-level project for remotely deploying software implants.','Not much is known about FREEFLOW. It is said to have four operational threads:\n\n1. The original FREEFLOW thread (early 2008), associated with [FORESTPLACE](/forestplace)/[FUSSYKEEL](/fussykeel).\n2. The [QUANTUM](/quantumtheory) thread.\n3. [FINGERGNOME](/fingergnome) high-to-low transfer.\n4. The new FREEFLOW 2.0 thread, associated with [FROZENEARTH](/frozenearth) covert infrastructure.','2015-01-15 04:37:46','2015-07-24 05:03:19'),(57,'FREEZEPOST','freezepost','An unknown tool within [TAO](/tao).','The only known mention of this tool is in a brief on the Texas Cryptologic Center (a.k.a. [BACONRIDGE](/baconridge)). This tool was designated for installation in November 2008 in room 137 at BACONRIDGE.','2015-01-15 04:37:52','2015-12-09 02:55:02'),(58,'FRIEZERAMP','friezeramp','A covert networking protocol in the [CHIMNEYPOOL](/chimneypool) framework.','FRIEZERAMP, also known as FRZ, is a secure, covert networking protocol similar to IPsec that works within the CHIMNEYPOOL framework. It only supports static network configuration. \n\nNodes in the FRIEZERAMP network are assigned a 4-byte FRZ address, usually represented in hexadecimal notation.','2015-01-15 04:38:18','2015-07-24 05:05:41'),(59,'FUNNELOUT','funnelout','A protocol for software exploits to call back to [C&C](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Command_and_control_(malware)) servers.','Little is known about this protocol. It\'s only mention comes in a presentation about [EGOTISTICALGIRAFFE](/egotisticalgiraffe), but the implication is that it used for exploits to call back to C&C servers. This particular callback does work against Tor, as opposed to [FINKDIFFERENT](/finkdifferent), which does not.','2015-01-15 04:38:25','2015-12-09 04:07:51'),(60,'GALAXY','galaxy','A program for find/fix/finish operations.','Little is known about this program.','2015-01-15 04:38:30','2015-12-09 04:26:43'),(61,'GECKO II','gecko-ii','An implant from the [ANT implant catalog](http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/NSA_ANT_catalog) that mates a hardware implant for covert wireless communications with a software implant for remote management.','This implant comprises a hardware implant such as as [WAGONBED](/wagonbed) and a software implant such as [IRONCHEF](/ironchef) to enable analysts to remotely monitor and maintain persistence of other software implants, even across air gaps.','2015-01-15 04:38:35','2015-12-08 22:48:28'),(62,'GENESIS','genesis','GENESIS is a device from the [ANT implant catalog](http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/NSA_ANT_catalog) that resembles a conventional cellular phone but contains capabilities such as monitoring and recording radio transmissions.','GENESIS is a commercial [GSM](http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/GSM) handset that has been modified to include a [Software Defined Radio (SDR)](http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Software-defined_radio) and additional system memory. The internal SDR allows a witting user to covertly perform network surveys, record RF spectrum, or perform handset location in hostile environments.\n\n**Disambiguation:** GENESIS may also refer to an [XKEYSCORE](/xkeyscore) tasking language. See [GENESIS (Language)](/genesis-language).\n\nThe GENESIS systems are designed to support covert operations in hostile environments. A witting user would be able to survey the local environment with the spectrum analyzer tool, select spectrum of interest to record, and download the spectrum information via the integrated ethernet to a laptop controller. The GENESIS system could also be used, in conjunction with an active interrogator, as the finishing tool when performing [Find/Fix/Finish](/find-fix-finish) operations in unconventional environments.\n\n#### Features\n\n* Concealed SDR with Handset Menu Interface\n* Spectrum Analyzer Capability\n* Find/Fix/Finish Capability\n* Integrated Ethernet\n* External Antenna Port\n* Internal 16 GB of storage\n* Multiple Integrated Antennas\n\n#### Future Enhancements\n\n* 3G Handset Host Platform\n* Additional Host Platforms\n* Increased Memory Capacity\n* Additional Find/Fix/Finish Capabilities\n* Active Interrogation Capabilities\n\nUnit Cost: $15,000','2015-01-15 04:39:03','2015-07-25 15:24:14'),(63,'GENIE','genie','A program for offensive cyber operations against foreign governments.','This program manages and oversees cyber operations (exploitation and attack). As of 2013, the program was estimated to have 85,000 devices under its control using a variety of implants from the [ANT implant catalog](http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/NSA_ANT_catalog).\n\nAs of 2013, the program employs 1,870 people and the budget is $651.7 million. It depends on both manual operations tailored to the specific target as well as automated exploitation via [TURBINE](/turbine). The TURBINE program is expected to dramatically increase the program\'s footprint.','2015-01-15 04:39:14','2015-12-09 01:02:16'),(65,'KONGUR','kongur','A software implant from the [ANT implant catalog](http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/NSA_ANT_catalog) that targets PCs running Microsoft Windows 9x, 2000, 2003, XP, or Vista.','The capabilities of this malware are unknown. Persistence is provided by a combination of the [BULLDOZER](/bulldozer) hardware implant and [GINSU](/ginsu) software implant.','2015-01-15 04:39:32','2015-12-09 04:35:04'),(66,'GINSU','ginsu','A software implant from the  [ANT implant catalog](http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/NSA_ANT_catalog) that provides persistence for the [KONGUR](/kongur) implant that targets any system with the PCI bus hardware implant [BULLDOZER](/bulldozer).','The implant supports any desktop PC that contains a PCI connector (for [BULLDOZER](/bulldozer) installation) and runs Microsoft Windows 9x, 2000, 2003, XP, or Vista. If KONGUR is removed from the target system, then BULLDOZER will reinstall it on the next system reboot.\n\n*Unit Cost:* $0','2015-01-15 04:39:42','2015-07-18 03:16:56'),(67,'GODSURGE','godsurge','A software implant from the [ANT implant catalog](http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/NSA_ANT_catalog) that runs on the [FLUXBABBITT](/fluxbabbit) hardware.','GODSURGE is used to provide persistence for a surveillance software implant. The GODSURGE software runs when ever the targeted system boots up, and it can also be configured to run periodically.','2015-01-15 04:39:47','2015-12-09 04:20:20'),(68,'GOPHERSET','gopherset','GOPHERSET is a software implant from the [ANT implant catalog](http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/NSA_ANT_catalog) that is loaded on to a [GSM](http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/GSM) [SIM card](http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Subscriber_identity_module) and can exfiltrate data from a mobile device.','GOPHERSET is a software implant for GSM (Global System for Mobile communication) subscriber identity module (SIM) cards. This implant pulls phonebook, SMS, and call log information from a target handset and exfiltrates it to a user-defined phone number via short message service (SMS).\n\nModern SIM cards (Phase 2+) have an application program interface known as the [SIM Toolkit (STK)](http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/SIM_Application_Toolkit). The STK has a suite of proactive commands that allow the SIM card to issue commands and make requests to the handset. GOPHERSET uses STK commands to retrieve the requested information and to exfiltrate data via SMS. After the GOPHERSET file is compiled, the program is loaded onto the SIM card using either a Universal Serial Bus (USB), smart card reader, or via over-the-air provisioning. In both cases, keys to the card may be required to install the application depending on the service provider\'s security configuration.\n\n*Unit Cost:* $0','2015-01-15 04:39:54','2015-01-18 01:40:04'),(69,'GOURMETTROUGH','gourmettrough','A persistence implant from the [ANT implant catalog](http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/NSA_ANT_catalog) that targets Juniper firewalls: nsg5t, ns50, ns25, isg1000, ssg140, ssg5, and ssg20.','When the router reboots, GOURMETTROUGH will install the [BANANAGLEE](/bananaglee) implant.','2015-01-15 04:41:01','2015-12-09 04:50:48'),(71,'HALLUXWATER','halluxwater','A persistence implant from the [ANT implant catalog](http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/NSA_ANT_catalog) that targets Huawei routers: Eudemon 200, 500, and 1000 series.','This implant provides persistence for [TURBOPANDA](/turbopanda). TURBOPANDA is re-installed every time the router reboots, and it survives OS upgrades and firmware upgrades.','2015-01-15 04:41:15','2015-12-09 05:07:53'),(72,'HAMMERMILL','hammermill','A remote management tool for the [HEADWATER](/headwater) persistent backdoor for Huawei routers.','This tool allows a remote operator to control the HEADWATER implant, which has the ability to capture and examine IP packets as they are being routed.','2015-01-15 04:41:22','2015-12-09 05:13:50'),(73,'HEADWATER','headwater','A software implant from the [ANT implant catalog](http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/NSA_ANT_catalog) that provides a persistent backdoor for select [Huawei](http://www.huawei.com/) routers.','The implant can be installed remotely by the NSA Remote Operations Center. (It is unclear what type of exploit is necessary for remote installation.)\n\nAfter installation, the backdoor implant is installed the router\'s firmware and will remain persistent even through power cycles.\n\nThe implant turns an infected router into a powerful surveillance device for all data being routed through it. Operators can control the router using the [HAMMERMILL](/hammermill) tool.','2015-01-15 04:41:38','2015-12-09 05:08:48'),(74,'HIGHLANDS','highlands','A [SIGAD](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/SIGINT_Activity_Designator) that designates signals collected from implants.','Not much is known about this SIGAD.','2015-01-15 04:41:44','2015-12-09 00:43:30'),(75,'HOLLOWPOINT','hollowpoint','A [software-defined radio (SDR)](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Software-defined_radio) module used in conjunction with [ENTOURAGE](/entourage).','HOLLOWPOINT consists of a [software-defined radio (SDR)](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Software-defined_radio) module used within ENTOURAGE. It connects to an antenna and a laptop to create a complete direction finding solution.','2015-01-15 04:41:49','2015-12-09 05:23:17'),(76,'HOWLERMONKEY','howlermonkey','HOWLERMONKEY is a radio frequency transceiver from the [ANT implant catalog](http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/NSA_ANT_catalog).','HOWLERMONKEY is a custom Short to Medium range implant RF Transceiver. It must be combined with a \"digital core\" — an embedded computer — to provide a complete implant.\n\nHOWLERMONKEY is a COTS-based transceiver deigned to be compatible with [CONJECTURE](/conjecture)/[SPECULATION](/speculation) networks and [STRIKEZONE](/strikezone) devices running a HOWLERMONKEY personality. PCB layouts are tailored to individual implant space requirements and can vary greatly in form factor.\n\n*Unit Cost:* $750-$1000','2015-01-15 04:41:56','2015-12-10 15:37:52'),(78,'IRATEMONK','iratemonk','A software implant from the [ANT implant catalog](http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/NSA_ANT_catalog) that provides persistence by modifying hard drive firmware.','The implant modifies the firmware of a supported hard drive so that the [master boot record (MBR)] (https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Master_boot_record) is replaced with a malicious bootloader at boot. Presence of the implant is well concealed: subsequent attempts to read the MBR will return the actual bootloader from disk, not the implant\'s bootloader. (For more information on hard drive firmware implants, see [SpriteMods.com Hard Disk Hacking Intro](http://spritesmods.com/?art=hddhack&page=1).)\n\nThe implant supports drives from a number of manufacturers, including [Western Digital](http://www.legitreviews.com/nsa-replacing-hard-drive-firmware-wd-denies-working-us-government_131762), Seagate, Maxtor, and Samsung.\n\nSimilar to [DEITYBOUNCE](/deitybounce), IRATEMONK does not contain surveillance functionality. It only provides stealth and persistence for another implant. The implant\'s capabilities also bear striking resemblance to the capabilities of the Equation Group, leading to [speculation](https://www.f-secure.com/weblog/archives/00002791.html) that the Equation Group _is the NSA_.\n\nThe implant is installed either via remote access exploit or supply chain interdiction. Installation is performed using [UNITEDRAKE](/unitedrake)/[STRAITBIZARRE](/straitbizarre) and [SLICKERVICAR](/slickervicar).\n\n*Unit Cost:* $0','2015-01-15 04:42:25','2015-07-17 03:51:43'),(79,'IRONCHEF','ironchef','A software implant from the [ANT implant catalog](http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/NSA_ANT_catalog) that provides persistence over an air gap.','IRONCHEF is used in conjunction with a hardware implant, such as [CROSSBEAM](/crossbeam) or [WAGONBED](/wagonbed). This implant provides remote access for the [ROC](/roc) so that analysts can monitor and re-install an adversarial software implant such as [UNITEDRAKE](/unitedrake). \n\nIRONCHEF is implanted in the [BIOS](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/BIOS) to maintain persistence and utilizes [System Management Mode](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/System_Management_Mode) to run code with high privileges where it cannot be seen by the host\'s operating system.','2015-01-15 04:42:55','2015-12-08 22:55:25'),(80,'ISLANDTRANSPORT','islandtransport','An \"enterprise message service.\"','This low-latency messaging protocol is used to send data from [TURMOIL](/turmoil) to [TURBINE](/turbine), known as \"tipping\" because TURMOIL tips off TURBINE when traffic matching a certain selector has been observed so that TURBINE can attempt exploitation.','2015-01-15 04:43:03','2015-07-25 19:41:10'),(81,'JETPLOW','jetplow','A software implant from the [ANT implant catalog](http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/NSA_ANT_catalog) that provides persistence for [Cisco PIX](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cisco_PIX) and ASA (Adaptive Security Appliance) firewalls.','The implant affects router firmware and provides persistence for the [BANANAGLEE](/bananaglee) implant. It also has stand-alone backdoor functionality. At boot time, the Cisco operating system is modified to include the BANANAGLEE payload, or if BANANAGLEE is not available, a backdoor is created so that BANANAGLEE can be installed later.\n\nIt supports Cisco\'s 500-series PIX firewalls as well as most ASA firewalls: 5505, 5510, 5520, 5540, and 5550. JETPLOW can be installed remotely if the firewall already contains the BANANAGLEE implant.\n\n*Unit Cost:* $0','2015-01-15 04:43:10','2015-07-17 04:02:02'),(82,'JUNIORMINT','juniormint','A very small computing platform from the [ANT implant catalog](http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/NSA_ANT_catalog) that is used to implement covert hardware implants.','The platform includes an ARM 9 CPU running at 400 Mhz, 32 MB of flash, 64 MB of SDRAM, and an [FPGA](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Field-programmable_gate_array) with 128MB of DDR2 RAM. The system can be built on a printed circuit board (PCB) or as a so-called \"flip chip\" for extra compactness.\n\nThis device appears to be the successor to [MAESTRO-II](/maestro-ii).\n\n*Unit cost:* Unknown','2015-01-15 04:43:21','2015-12-09 15:16:06'),(83,'LANDSHARK','landshark','An implant from the [ANT implant catalog](http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/NSA_ANT_catalog).','Little is known about this implant. It is mentioned in the ANT catalog entry for [EBSR](/ebsr) next to [CANDYGRAM](/candygram). ','2015-01-15 04:43:47','2015-12-09 05:48:54'),(86,'LFS-2','lfs-2','A processing system in the [ANT implant catalog](http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/NSA_ANT_catalog)  that decodes a baseband video signal from [PHOTOANGLO](/photoanglo).','Little is known about this system.','2015-01-15 04:44:03','2015-12-09 05:54:22'),(88,'LIFESAVER','lifesaver','A [SIGAD](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/SIGINT_Activity_Designator) that designates signals collected from hard drive imaging.','Not much is known about this SIGAD.','2015-01-15 04:44:16','2015-12-09 00:52:40'),(89,'LOUDAUTO','loudauto','An audio-based retroreflector from the [ANT implant catalog](http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/NSA_ANT_catalog).','This is a covert microphone that converts sound into a [pulse-position modulation (PPM)](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pulse-position_modulation) digital waveform using a fixed frequency. This signal switches a [field-effect transistor (FET)](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Field-effect_transistor) on and off. \n\nThe implant can be remotely \"illuminated\" using a continuous wave (CW) signal from a nearby radar unit. The CW signal is amplitude-modulated with the PPM wave and re-radiated, where it can be remotely received and processed.\n\nThis is part of the [ANGRYNEIGHBOR](/angryneighbor) family of radar retro-reflectors. all of the components used on this device and in the post-processing hardware are commercially available components that are not attributable to the NSA.','2015-01-15 04:44:25','2015-12-09 15:06:30'),(90,'MAESTRO II','maestro-ii','A very small computing platform from the [ANT implant catalog](http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/NSA_ANT_catalog)  that is used to implement covert hardware implants.','Smaller than a quarter, MAESTRO-II is a microcontroller platform that includes an ARM 7 CPU running at 66Mhz, 4MB of flash, 8MB of SDRAM, and an FPGA.\n\nThis unit is the successor to [MAESTRO](/maestro). It was succeeded by [JUNIORMINT](/juniormint) in 2009.\n\n*Unit Cost:* $3,000-4,000','2015-01-15 04:45:00','2015-12-09 15:20:14'),(91,'MIDDLEMAN','middleman','An intermediate tool for managing communications links for [STRAITBIZARRE](/straitbizarre) shooters.','This tool is used by [GENIE NCC](/genie-ncc) as a go-between for managing communications links for STRAITBIZARRE shooters.','2015-01-15 04:45:16','2015-07-24 05:32:56'),(92,'MINERALIZE','mineralize','A [SIGAD](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/SIGINT_Activity_Designator) that designates signals collected from a LAN implant.','Not much is known about this SIGAD.','2015-01-15 04:45:23','2015-12-09 00:50:30'),(93,'MJOLNIR','mjolnir','An alternative [Tor](https://www.torproject.org/) client developed by the NSA for research and adversarial purposes.','Named after the hammer of Norse god\'s Thor — note the similarity to \"Tor\" — Mjolnir is a Tor client library that is designed to be indistinguishable from Tor on the network. The client library allows manipulation of parts of the Tor protocol and process that the original Tor client does not, such as building arbitrary length circuits. This library does not implement any attacks itself; it is merely a foundation for building attacks against Tor.','2015-01-15 04:45:32','2015-12-09 03:54:57'),(94,'MOCCASIN','moccasin','A hardware implant from the [ANT implant catalog](http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/NSA_ANT_catalog) that is embedded in a USB keyboard.','MOCCASIN is a version of [COTTONMOUTH-I](/cottonmouth-i) where the USB implant is permanently attached to a USB keyboard.','2015-01-15 04:45:38','2015-12-09 15:28:34'),(95,'MONKEYCALENDAR','monkeycalendar','A software implant from the [ANT implant catalog](http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/NSA_ANT_catalog) that targets [GSM](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/GSM) [SIM cards](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Subscriber_identity_module).','This implant is installed on the SIM card of a target\'s cell phone. It can pull geolocation information from the device and exfiltrate it to a predefined number using encrypted [SMS](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Short_Message_Service).\n\nThis implant makes use of the standard [SIM Application Toolkit (STK)](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/SIM_Application_Toolkit) software library present on all modern cell phones. The implant can be installed by inserting the SIM card into a USB smartcard reader or by over-the-air provisioning.','2015-01-15 04:45:44','2015-12-09 15:37:12'),(98,'NEBULA','nebula','NEBULA is a \"network-in-a-box\" device from the [ANT implant catalog](http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/NSA_ANT_catalog).','NEBULA is a multi-protocol, macro-class Network-In-a-Box (NIB) system. Leverages the existing [Typhon GUI](/typhon) and supports [GSM](http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/GSM), [UMTS](http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Universal_Mobile_Telecommunications_System), [CDMA2000](http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Code_division_multiple_access) applications. [LTE](http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/LTE_(telecommunication)) is capability currently under development.\n\n#### Features\n\n* Dual Carrier System\n* EGSM 900MHz\n* UMTS 2100MHz\n* CDMA2000 1900MHz\n* Macro-class Base station\n* 32+Km Range\n* Optional Battery Kits\n* Highly Mobile and Deployable\n* Integrated GPS, MS, & 802.11\n* Voice & High-speed Data\n\n#### Advanced Features\n\n* GPS – Supporting NEBULA applications\n* Designed to be self-configuring with security and encryption features\n* 802.11 – Supports high speed wireless LAN remote command and control\n\n#### Enclosure\n\n* 8.5\"H x 13.0\"W x 16.5\"D\n* Approximately 45 lbs\n* Actively cooled for extreme environments\n\n#### NEBULA System Kit\n\n* NEBULA System\n* 3 Interchangeable RF bands\n* AC/DC power converter\n* Antenna to support MS, GPS, WIFI, & RF\n* LAN, RF, & USB cables\n* Pelican Case\n* (Field Kit only) Control Laptop and Accessories\n\n#### Separately Priced Options\n\n* 1500 WH LiIon Battery Kit\n\n#### Base Station Router Platform\n\n* Multiple BSR units can be interconnected to form a macro network using 802.3 and 802.11 back-haul.\n* Future GPRS and HSDPA data service and associated application\n\n*Unit Cost:* $250,000','2015-01-15 04:47:38','2015-01-18 02:54:11'),(100,'NIGHTSTAND','nightstand','A wireless exploitation and injection tool from the [ANT implant catalog](http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/NSA_ANT_catalog).','This hardware device targets [802.11 wireless networks](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/IEEE_802.11). The device contains a standard laptop running [Linux Fedora Core 3](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fedora_(operating_system)) with radio frequency (RF) equipment and an antenna packaged into a portable carrying case. It targets Windows 2000 and Windows XP (including SP1 and SP2) running Internet Explorer 5.0 or 6.0. It target one or more wireless targets simultaneously, and the attack is undetectable to the end user.\n\nWhen combined with external amplifiers and antennas, NIGHTSTAND can attack targets as far as 8 miles away.\n\n*Unit Cost:* Unknown','2015-01-15 04:47:49','2015-12-09 15:44:14'),(101,'NIGHTWATCH','nightwatch','A processing system in the [ANT implant catalog](http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/NSA_ANT_catalog)  that decodes a baseband video signal from [PHOTOANGLO](/photoanglo).','Little is known about this system.','2015-01-15 04:47:55','2015-12-09 05:54:25'),(102,'OCEAN','ocean','A [SIGAD](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/SIGINT_Activity_Designator) that designates signals collected from an \"optical collection system for raster-based computer screens.\"','Not much is known about this SIGAD.','2015-01-15 04:47:59','2015-12-09 00:51:29'),(105,'OLYMPUSFIRE','olympusfire','A trojan for computers running Microsoft Windows.','This trojan supplants [VALIDATOR](/validator). The implant will contact a listening post (LP) server for tasks, execute each task, and return the results. It offers operators the ability to send and receive files, get information about the system, and map out local network topography.','2015-01-15 04:48:33','2015-07-25 20:25:08'),(106,'OMNIGAT','omnigat','An unknown item in the [ANT implant catalog](http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/NSA_ANT_catalog).','The nature or capabilities of this item are unknown. It\'s only known mention is in the concept of operations diagram for [GINSU](/ginsu).','2015-01-15 04:48:39','2015-12-09 15:47:19'),(108,'PARCHDUSK','parchdusk','An unknown operation or program based at the Texas Cryptologic Center, a.k.a. [BACONRIDGE](/baconridge).','Little is known about this program. It\'s only mention is in a presentation about BACONRIDGE and [TAO](/tao).','2015-01-15 04:49:26','2015-12-09 15:50:59'),(109,'PHOTOANGLO','photoanglo','PHOTOANGLO is a radar unit from the [ANT implant catalog](http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/NSA_ANT_catalog) that is used to illuminate passive implants. It is an improved version of the [CTX4000](/ctx4000).','PHOTOANGLO is a joint NSA/GCHQ project to develop a new radar system to take the place of the [CTX4000](/ctx4000).\n\n#### Capabilities\n\nThe planned capabilities for this system are:\n\n* Frequency range: 1 - 2 GHz, which will be later extended to 1 - 4 GHz\n* Maximum bandwidth: 450 MHz.\n* Size: Small enough to fit into a slim briefcase.\n* Weight: Less than 10 lbs.\n* Maximum Output Power: 2W\n* Output:\n  * Video\n  * Transmit antenna\n* Inputs:\n  * External oscillator\n  * Receive antenna\n\n#### Concept of Operation\n\nThe radar unit generates an un-modulated, continuous wave (CW) signal. The oscillator is either generated internally, or externally through a signal generator or cavity oscillator. The unit amplifies the signal and sends it out to an RF connector, where it is directed to some form of transmission antenna (horn, parabolic dish, LPA, spiral). \n\nRadar illumination is used to gather data from passive implants that do not otherwise produce strong radio frequency signals; the system behaves in a manner similar to [RFID](http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Radio-frequency_identification). The signal illuminates the target system and is re-radiated. \n\nThe receive antenna picks up the re-radiated signal and directs the signal to the receive input. The signal is amplified, filtered, and mixed with the transmit antenna. The result is a homodyne receiver in which the RF signal is mixed directly to baseband. The baseband video signal is ported to an external BNC connector. This connects to a processing system, such as [NIGHTWATCH](/nightwatch), an [LFS-2](/lfs-2), or [VIEWPLATE](/viewplate), to process the signal and provide the intelligence.\n\n*Unit Cost:* $40,000','2015-01-15 04:49:35','2015-01-18 04:23:12'),(110,'PICASSO','picasso','A modified cell phone from the [ANT implant catalog](http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/NSA_ANT_catalog).','PICASSO is a modified cell phone ([GSM](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/GSM)) handset that can collect user and location data, or eavesdrop using the handset\'s built-in microphone.\n\nIt collects the following types of data:\n\n* Incoming/outgoing call numbers\n* Recently registered networks\n* Recent location area codes (LACs)\n* Recently assigned [TMSI](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mobility_management#TMSI)/[IMSI](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/International_mobile_subscriber_identity)\n* Recently entered pin numbers\n* \"Hot mic\" to receive audio from the built-in microphone\n* \n\nThe device can be used to track and target adversaries. It can also be carried by an agency asset. It has a \"panic button\" for use in the latter scenario, which sends a distress signal and the user\'s current location to a listening post (LP) operator. The device can also selectively block calls in order to deny cell phone service to the target.\n\nIt can be installed in the following commercial cell phone models:\n\n* Eastcom 760 C+\n* Samsung E600\n* Samsung X450\n* Samsung C140\n\n*Unit Cost:* $2,000 (approx.)','2015-01-15 04:49:40','2015-12-09 16:02:02'),(112,'QFIRE','qfire','A project that combines [TURMOIL](/turmoil) passive surveillance with the [TURBINE](/turbine) command and control system.','The QFIRE project involves collocating [QUANTUM](/quantumtheory) components at TURMOIL collection points. Because QUANTUM often relies on low network latency to carry out a [man-on-the-side attack](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Man-on-the-side_attack), placing QUANTUM components at collection points improves attack success rates by greatly reducing network latency.','2015-01-15 04:49:56','2015-07-24 06:09:32'),(114,'QUANTUM INSERT','quantum-insert','A [man-on-the-side](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Man-on-the-side_attack) technique used in the [QUANTUM](/quantumtheory) framework.','This technique requires the ability to monitor internet traffic of a target. When the target makes a request to a web server, QUANTUM INSERT shoots its payload in a race to beat the response from the legitimate server.','2015-01-15 04:50:14','2015-07-24 06:06:54'),(115,'QUANTUMBOT','quantumbot','A program within [QUANTUM](/quantumtheory) that takes over botnets created by criminal enterprises or other nation states and repurposes them for agency use.','This program is a part of the [TURBULENCE](/turbulence) program and integrates with [TURMOIL](/turmoil) to passively locate botnet nodes and [TURBINE](/turbine) to exploit/manage them.\n\nThis program has many benefits to the agency:\n\n* Significant scale for relatively low cost.\n* Nodes in the botnet may have advantageous network position for specific operations.\n* Nodes in the network are non-attributable to the agency and are considered disposable.\n\nAs of 2007, the agency had achieved control of 140,000 nodes using this program. A briefing on the program identifies many limitations and flaws with the program, however, indicating that it may not be as successful as expected.\n\nThis program apparently coordinates with the FBI; it\'s unclear if some botnets are referred to the FBI for investigation, or if the FBI refers botnets to the NSA for exploitation. ','2015-01-15 04:50:21','2015-12-09 16:43:17'),(116,'QUANTUMCOOKIE','quantumcookie','A program within [QUANTUM](/quantumtheory) that deanonymizes [Tor](https://www.torproject.org/) users.','QUANTUMCOOKIE is a simple means to deanonymize some Tor users. It works by monitoring post-exit traffic, e.g. by running an adversarial Tor exit node or by simply using privileged network position, e.g. QUANTUMTHEORY, to monitor traffic.\n\nWhen a Tor user requests a plaintext site, QUANTUMCOOKIE responds with a redirect to a service such as Hotmail or Yahoo, which as of 2012 do not use secure cookies. The user\'s browser will send the corresponding cookies in plaintext, where they can easily be observed by QUANTUMTHEORY.','2015-01-15 04:50:37','2015-12-09 16:38:26'),(117,'QUANTUMCOPPER','quantumcopper','A program within [QUANTUM](/quantumtheory) that corrupts file uploads & downloads.','Little is known about this program. It\'s only known mention is in a presentation on QUANTUM.','2015-01-15 04:50:50','2015-12-09 16:44:25'),(118,'QUANTUMNATION','quantumnation','A man-on-the-side exploitation technique similar to [QUANTUMTHEORY](/quantumtheory) but it deploys an impermanent software implant.','QUANTUMNATION deploys a \"stage 0\" implant called [SEASONEDMOTH](/seasonedmoth) that automtically removes itself after a period of time. In contrast, QUANTUMTHEORY deploys a permanent \"stage 1\" implant, e.g. [VALIDATOR](/validator) or [COMMONDEER](/commondeer).\n\nIn any case, the implant has no surveillance functions; its only purpose is to facilitate the installation of a more advanced software implant.','2015-01-15 04:50:57','2015-12-09 02:10:01'),(119,'QUANTUMSKY','quantumsky','A program within [QUANTUM](/quantumtheory) that resets TCP connections.','Little is known about this program. It\'s only known mention is in a presentation on QUANTUM. \n\nPresumably this program is used as a targeted denial-of-service.','2015-01-15 04:51:06','2015-12-09 16:45:19'),(120,'QUANTUMTHEORY','quantumtheory','A [man-on-the-side](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Man-on-the-side_attack) protocol injection technique that can be active or passive. (a.k.a. QUANTUM)','QUANTUM servers are placed at strategic locations on the internet backbone, utilizing partnerships between the intelligence community and telecommunications companies. These sensitive locations allow QUANTUM servers to respond to requests more quickly than the intended recipient. The quick response time allows QUANTUM to perform a man-on-the-side attack.\n\nQUANTUM is a large, complex system incorporating the following components:\n\n* [TURMOIL:](/turmoil) passive sensor\n* [TURBINE:](/turbine) mission logic for remote agents\n* [ISLANDTRANSPORT:](/islandtransport) messaging fabric\n* [SURPLUSHANGER:](/surplushanger) high→low data diodes\n* [STRAITBIZARRE](/straitbizarre): NSA implant/shooter\n* DAREDEVIL: GHCQ implant/shooter\n\nQUANTUM has many functional areas:\n\n* [QUANTUMINSERT:](/quantuminsert) HTML redirection\n* [QUANTUMSKY:](/quantumsky) HTML/TCP resets\n* [QUANTUMBOT:](/quantumbot) IRC botnet hijacking\n* [QUANTUMBISCUIT:](/quantumbiscuit)\n    * Redirection based on keywork\n    * Mostly HTML cookie values\n* [QUANTUMDNS:](/quantumdns)\n    * DNS hijacking\n    * Caching nameservers\n* [QUANTUMBOT2:](/quantumbot2)\n    * Combination of Q-BOT/Q-BISCUIT for web based command and control botnets\n* [QUANTUMCOPPER:](/quantumcopper) File download disruption\n* [QUANTUMMUSH:](/quantummush) Virtual HUFFMUSH / targeted spam exploitation\n* [QUANTUMSPIN:](/quantumspin) Instant messaging (MSN chat, XMPP)\n* [QUANTUMSQUEEL:](/quantumsqueel) injection into MySQL database connections\n* [QUANTUMSQUIRREL:](/quantumsquirrel) use any possible IP address','2015-01-15 04:52:02','2015-12-09 01:56:16'),(122,'RADON','radon','A bi-directional \"host tap\" that can read and inject packets on an Ethernet network.','Little is known about this implant.\n\nPierluigi Paganini of Infosec Institute speculates that RADON was initially developed by [Netragrad](http://www.netragard.com/) and later acquired by the NSA. Netragard had created a malware package called RADON that was used for penetration testing. A now-deleted blog post (saved by The Internet Archive) describes how the RADON malware was undetectable by any antivirus program and was deployed in one instance via physical access to a USB port.','2015-01-15 04:52:18','2015-12-09 01:42:23'),(123,'RAGEMASTER','ragemaster','ENTOURAGE is a VGA cable implant from the [ANT implant catalog](http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/NSA_ANT_catalog) used for remotely monitoring what\'s being displayed on a computer screen.','RAGEMASTER is an RF retro-reflector that provides an enhanced radar cross-section for [VAGRANT](/vagrant) collection. It\'s concealed in a standard computer video graphics array (VGA) cable between the video card and the video monitor. It\'s typically installed in the ferrite on the video cable.\n\n#### Capabilities\nRAGEMASTER provides a target for RF flooding and allows for easier collection of the VAGRANT video signal. The current RAGEMASTER unit taps the red video line on the VGA cable. It was found that, empirically, this provides the best video return and cleanest readout of the monitor contents.\n\n#### Concept of Operation\nThe RAGEMASTER taps the red video line between the video card within the desktop unit and the computer monitor, typically an LCD. When the RAGEMASTER is illuminated by a radar unit, the illuminating signal is modulated with the red video information. This information is re-radiated, where it is picked up at the radar, demodulated, and passed onto the processing unit, such as a LFS-2 and an external monitor, [NIGHTWATCH](/nightwatch), [GOTHAM](/gotham), or [VIEWPLATE](/viewplate). The processor recreates the horizontal and vertical sync of the targeted monitor, thus allowing [TAO](http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Tailored_Access_Operations) personnel to see what is displayed on the targeted monitor.\n\n*Unit Cost:* $30','2015-01-15 04:52:27','2015-01-18 04:18:25'),(124,'REMATION II','remation-ii','An NSA/GCHQ joint workshop to analyze [Tor](https://www.torproject.org/) and study exploitation options.','This was a 2 week workshop sometime during or before 2007 where the two agencies studied and analyzed Tor to determine what types of information could be collected and what types of exploits were possible. During the workshop, GCHQ analysts set up an unknown number of Tor nodes running on [Amazon Web Services](https://aws.amazon.com/).','2015-01-15 04:52:34','2015-12-09 16:50:39'),(125,'RETURNSPRING','returnspring','An unknown component in the [WISTFULTOLL](/wistfultoll) concept of operations diagram from the [ANT implant catalog](http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/NSA_ANT_catalog).','This appears to be some intermediary tool that sits between a [ROC](/roc) analyst and the WISTFULTOLL forensics tool. It runs exclusively on the high side.','2015-01-15 04:52:45','2015-12-09 16:54:18'),(126,'ROCKYKNOB','rockyknob','A [digital signal processor (DSP)](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Digital_signal_processor) from the [ANT implant catalog](http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/NSA_ANT_catalog).','This DSP is an optional component in the [CROSSBEAM](/crossbeam) module. It is used to transmit data over a [GSM](/gsm) voice connection, using a data-over-voice technique.','2015-01-15 04:52:55','2015-12-09 16:57:57'),(127,'RONIN','ronin','A program that tracks [Tor](https://www.torproject.org/) nodes.','This system tracks the \"last seen\" timestamp for each Tor node that it observes. It does not have a precise method to estimate when Tor nodes leave the network, so it automatically ages off Tor nodes if they have not been seen in a long time.','2015-01-15 04:53:01','2015-12-09 17:09:53'),(128,'SCHOOLMONTANA','schoolmontana','A persistence implant from the [ANT implant catalog](http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/NSA_ANT_catalog) that targets Juniper J series routers.','This implant supports all modern versions of [Junos OS](http://www.juniper.net/us/en/products-services/nos/junos/). The implant modifies the [BIOS](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/BIOS) and uses the [System Management Mode](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/System_Management_Mode) to maintain persistence across reboots and/or upgrades.\n\nThis implant is intended to persist the [VALIDATOR](/validator) software implant.','2015-01-15 04:53:09','2015-12-09 17:14:03'),(130,'SEASONEDMOTH','seasonedmoth','A \"stage 0\" implant deployed by [QUANTUMNATION](/quantumnation).','Similar to [COMMONDEER](/commondeer), except that SEASONEDMOTH automatically removes itself after 30 days unless it is explicitly requested to extend its life.','2015-01-15 04:53:25','2015-12-09 02:05:36'),(132,'SHARPFOCUS','sharpfocus','An unknown operation or program based at the Texas Cryptologic Center, a.k.a. [BACONRIDGE](/baconridge).','Little is known about this program. It\'s only mention is in a presentation about BACONRIDGE and [TAO](/tao).','2015-01-15 04:53:56','2015-12-09 15:51:02'),(133,'SHORTSHEET','shortsheet','An unknown computer network exploitation (CNE) tool or technique.','The only known mention of SHORTSHEET is in a presentation about [Tor](https://www.torproject.org/). The presentation notes that SHORTSHEET does not work against the Tor Browser Bundle because of TorButton, a plugin that disables most types of active content such as JavaScript.','2015-01-15 04:54:01','2015-12-09 20:13:45'),(134,'SIERRAMONTANA','sierramontana','A persistence implant from the [ANT implant catalog](http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/NSA_ANT_catalog) that targets Juniper M-series routers.','This implant is installed in the [BIOS](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/BIOS) and uses [System Management Mode](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/System_Management_Mode) to automatically re-install a software implant whenever the router reboots. \n\nIt is intended to provide persistence for [VALIDATOR](/validator).\n\n*Unit cost:* Unknown','2015-01-15 04:54:08','2015-12-09 20:18:35'),(135,'SLICKERVICAR','slickervicar','A tool from the [ANT implant catalog](http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/NSA_ANT_catalog) that targets hard drives manufactured by Western Digital, Seagate, Maxtor, and Samsung.','The only known mention of SLICKERVICAR is in the ANT catalog entry for [IRATEMONK](/iratemonk). This appears to be an installation tool to implant IRATEMONK into the hard drive\'s firmware.','2015-01-15 04:55:38','2015-12-09 20:23:04'),(136,'SOMBERKNAVE','somberknave','SOMBERKNAVE is a software implant for Windows PCs from the [ANT implant catalog](http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/NSA_ANT_catalog) that surreptitiously jumps air gaps.','SOMBERKNAVE is a Windows XP software implant that surreptitiously routes TCP traffic from a designated process to a secondary network via an unused embedded 802.11 network device. If an Internet-connected wireless Access Point is present, SOMBERKNAVE can be used to allow [OLYMPUS](/olympus) or [VALIDATOR](/validator) to \"call home\" via 802.11 from an air-gapped target computer. If the 802.11 interface is in use by the target, SOMBERKNAVE will not attempt to transmit.\n\nOperationally, VALIDATOR initiates a call home. SOMBERKNAVE triggers from the named event and tries to associate with an access point. If connection is successful, data is sent over 802.11 to the ROC. VALIDATOR receives instructions, downloads OLYMPUS, then disassociates and gives up control of the 802.11 hardware. OLYMPUS will then be able to communicate with the Remote Operator Console (ROC) via SOMBERKNAVE, as long as there is an available access point.\n\n*Unit Cost:* $50,000\n','2015-01-15 04:55:48','2015-01-17 23:16:55'),(137,'SOUFFLETROUGH','souffletrough','A persistence implant from the [ANT implant catalog](http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/NSA_ANT_catalog) that targets Juniper firewalls: SSG 300 and 500 series.','When the router reboots, SOUFFLETROUGH will install the [BANANAGLEE](/bananaglee) implant.','2015-01-15 04:55:53','2015-12-09 04:50:56'),(138,'SPARROW II','sparrow-ii','An embedded computer designed for running [BLINDDATE](/blinddate) software.','This small form factor computer contains an IBM PowerPC 405GPR processor, 64MB of SDRAM, and 16MB of flash. It has 4 mini-PCI slots to add support for USB, 802.11, or Compact Flash. The computer runs a Linux operating system. It has a battery life of 2 hours.\n\n*Unit cost:* $6,000','2015-01-15 04:55:59','2015-12-09 20:27:15'),(139,'SPECULATION','speculation','A radio frequency (RF) communications protocol used by [HOWLERMONKEY](/howlermonkey).','This protocol is used in implants such as HOWLERMONKEY to enable RF communications, possibly for bridging an air gapped network, or for multiple nearby implants to communicate with each other covertly.','2015-01-15 04:56:05','2015-12-09 15:30:55'),(140,'STEELFLAUTA','steelflauta','A [SIGAD](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/SIGINT_Activity_Designator) that designates signals collected from [TAO](/tao).','Little is known about this SIGAD.','2015-01-15 04:56:15','2015-12-09 02:41:51'),(141,'STRAITBIZARRE','straitbizarre','A cross platform implant built using the [CHIMNEYPOOL](/chimneypool) framework in the [QUANTUM](/quantumtheory) architecture.','The implant (also known as SBZ) is compatible with Linux and Windows. It focuses on file exfiltration from endpoint devices. It uses the [FRIEZERAMP](/friezeramp) covert networking protocol for exfiltration.\n\nSTRAITBIZARRE can retain data until a reliable network link is available, then send data securely and covertly. It is an example of delay-tolerant networking (DTN). The implant allows for exfiltration of data from systems that are otherwise inaccessible or would require physical access.\n\nAlternatively, STRAITBIZARRE can be used as a \"shooter\": a disposable, non-attributable node that infects and implant nearby devices. In this configuration, the implant receives instructions from the [TURBINE](/turbine) command and control system via [SURPLUSHANGAR](/surplushangar) diodes. ','2015-01-15 04:56:26','2015-12-09 02:13:47'),(142,'STRIKEZONE','strikezone','An unknown radio frequency (RF) device in the [ANT implant catalog](http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/NSA_ANT_catalog).','The only mention of this device is in the ANT catalog entry for [HOWLERMONKEY](/howlermonkey), which implies that STRIKEZONE is an RF device, possibly the receiver for a HOWLERMONKEY implant.','2015-01-15 04:56:30','2015-12-09 20:34:08'),(143,'STRONGMITE','strongmite','Control software used by the [ROC](/roc) for managing software implants.','Not much is known about STRONGMITE. The ROC apparently uses this software for managing and re-deploying software implants. Its existence was revealed in the [ANT implant catalog](http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/NSA_ANT_catalog) entry for [IRONCHEF](/ironchef).','2015-01-15 04:56:36','2015-12-08 22:59:53'),(144,'STUCCOMONTANA','stuccomontana','A persistence implant from the [ANT implant catalog](http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/NSA_ANT_catalog) that targets Juniper T-series routers.','This implant is installed in the [BIOS](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/BIOS) and uses [System Management Mode](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/System_Management_Mode) to automatically re-install a software implant whenever the router reboots. \n\nIt is intended to provide persistence for [VALIDATOR](/validator).\n\n*Unit cost:* Unknown','2015-01-15 04:56:40','2015-12-09 20:40:28'),(145,'STUXNET','stuxnet','A computer virus co-authored by the NSA and Israeli intelligence that targeted Iranian nuclear enrichment facilities in Nantanz.','Released in 2010, the virus affected centrifuges used to enrich uranium gas at the Natanz facility. The initial infection is believed to have been conducted by passing malicious USB drives to workers at the facility. These workers unwittingly introduced the virus to the nuclear enrichment plant when they plugged an infected USB drive into any computer in the facility. From there, the virus spread throughout the facility, specifically targeting the [Siemens](http://www.siemens.com/) programmable logic controllers (PLCs) that run the centrifuges.\n\nThe virus was notable at the time for an exceptional level of sophistication. Containing four zero-day exploits, observers were certain that it was the work of a nation state. These suspicions were later confirmed by an Edward Snowden in an interview published in Der Spiegel.','2015-01-15 04:56:45','2015-12-09 20:54:53'),(146,'SURLYSPAWN','surlyspawn','SURLYSPAWN is a keyboard logger from the [ANT implant catalog](http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/NSA_ANT_catalog) that transmits keystrokes using an RF retro-reflector.','SURLYSPAWN is a data RF retro-reflector. It provides return modulated with target data (keyboard or other low data rate digital device) when illuminated with radar. It is similar to an [RFID](http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Radio-frequency_identification) system, but on a larger scale.\n\nSURLYSPAWN has the capability to gather keystrokes without requiring any software running on the targeted system. It also only requires that the targeted system be touched once. The retro-reflector is compatible with both USB and PS/2 keyboards. The simplicity of the design allows the form factor to be tailored for specific operational requirements. Future capabilities will include laptop keyboards.\n\nThe board taps into the data line from the keyboard to the processor. The board generates a square wave oscillating at a preset frequency. The data-line signal is used to shift the square wave frequency higher or lower, depending on the level of the data-line signal. The square wave, in essence, becomes frequency shift keyed (FSK). When the unit is illuminated by a CW signal from a nearby radar, the illuminating signal is amplitude-modulated (AM) with this square wave. The signal is re-radiated, where it is received by the radar, demodulated, and the demodulated signal is processed to recover the keystrokes. SURLYSPAWN is part of the [ANGRYNEIGHBOR](/angryneighbor) family of radar retro-reflectors.\n\n*Unit Cost:* $30','2015-01-15 04:56:50','2015-01-17 06:28:48'),(147,'SURPLUSHANGAR','surplushangar','A high-to-low [data diode](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Unidirectional_network).','Not much is known about this product. It is used for restricting traffic between \"high\" (i.e. classified) networks and \"low\" (i.e. sensitive but unclassified).','2015-01-15 04:57:02','2015-07-24 05:21:44'),(148,'SUTURESAILOR','suturesailor','An embedded computer from the [ANT implant catalog](http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/NSA_ANT_catalog).','SUTURESAILOR is a small computer on a printed circuit board (PCB) that is paired with a radio frequency transceiver, such as [HOWLERMONKEY](/howlermonkey), to create a fully functional implant.','2015-01-15 04:57:10','2015-12-09 20:58:52'),(149,'SWAP','swap','A BIOS implant from the [ANT implant catalog](http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/NSA_ANT_catalog).','SWAP provides a persistent exploit on a computer by infecting the motherboard\'s [BIOS](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/BIOS) and the hard drive\'s [Host Protected Area (HPA)](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Host_protected_area) in order to run code before the operating system even loads.\n\n#### Supported Operating Systems\n\n* Windows\n* Linux\n* FreeBSD\n* Solaris\n\n#### Supported File Systems\n\n* FAT32\n* NTFS\n* EXT2\n* EXT3\n* UFS 1.0\n\nSWAP is installed on a target computer either through supply chain interdiction or via some remote access exploit. [ARKSTREAM](/arkstream) is used to to reflash the BIOS\nand [TWISTEDKILT](/twistedkilt) is used to overwrite the hard drive\'s HPA.\n\n*Unit Cost*: $0','2015-01-15 04:57:20','2015-07-15 05:10:49'),(150,'TAWDRYYARD','tawdryyard','A radio frequency (RF) retroreflector from the [ANT implant catalog](http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/NSA_ANT_catalog).','TAWDRYYARD is used as a beacon to locate deployed [RAGEMASTER](/ragemaster) implants. The unit outputs a square wave. When illuminated with radar, the illuminating signal is amplitude modulated with the square wave and is re-radiated where it can be picked up by the radar unit. The unit\'s presence can be detected by a frequency spectrum analyzer and the presence of energy at TAWDRYYARD\'s preset frequency.\n\nThe unit uses a coin battery that can last for months or years. It less than 1/4\" long. It can be detected within a 50 ft. radius. All of the parts used are commercially available and non-attributable to the NSA.','2015-01-15 04:57:29','2015-12-09 21:25:00'),(151,'TOTECHASER','totechaser','A [Windows CE](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Windows_CE) implant targeting the [Thuraya 2520](http://www.thuraya.com/userfiles/files/Thuraya%20SG/Brochure/Thuraya%20SG_2520_Jun2010.pdf) handset from the [ANT implant catalog](http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/NSA_ANT_catalog).','The Thuraya is a dual mode phone that can operate in [SAT](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Satellite_phone) or [GSM](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/GSM) modes. It also sports a [GPRS](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/General_Packet_Radio_Service) data connection for web browsing, e-mail, and [MMS](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Multimedia_Messaging_Service) messages.\n\nThe TOTECHASER implant can retrieve GSM and GPS location data from the handset, as well as call log, contacts, and other user information. The implant can remotely command, control, and exfiltrate data from the phone using [SMS](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Short_Message_Service) as a covert channel.\n\nThis implant is installed on a target device via supply chain interdiction, but remote exploits are being researched.\n\n*Unit Cost*: Not Specified','2015-01-15 04:57:37','2015-07-15 05:18:23'),(152,'TOTEGHOSTLY 2.0','toteghostly-2-0','A [STRAITBIZARRE](/straitbizarre) implant from the [ANT implant catalog](http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/NSA_ANT_catalog) for the Windows Mobile operating system.','This implant uses the [CHIMNEYPOOL](/chimneypool) framework and is compliant with [FREEFLOW](/freeflow) and works in the [TURBULENCE](/turbulence) architecture.\n\nThe implant has a modular design that allows a remote operator to push a variety of different tasks to the implant, including:\n\n* Push or pull files to or from the device\n* Retrieve SMS messages sent or received\n* Retrieve contacts\n* Retrieve voicemail messages\n* Geolocation or cell tower location\n* \"Hot mic\", i.e. use the built-in microphone to record audio from the room\n* Record pictures from the built-in camera\n\nCommand and control can be performed over [SMS](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Short_Message_Service) or [GPRS](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/General_Packet_Radio_Service). A [FRIEZERAMP](/friezeramp) module can be used for covert communications.\n\nInstallation requires physical access but (as of 2008) remote installation is a capability that is being developed.','2015-01-15 04:57:49','2015-12-09 21:36:11'),(153,'TRINITY','trinity','A very small, embedded computer from the [ANT implant catalog](http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/NSA_ANT_catalog).','Trinity is a very small computer (the size of a penny) that contains an ARM 9 CPU running at 180Mhz, 4MB flash, 96 MB SDRAM, and an FPGA. This computer must be combined with a radio frequency (RF) module like [HOWLERMONKEY](/howlermonkey) to make a complete implant.\n\n*Unit cost:* $6,250 (minimum order 100)','2015-01-15 04:58:00','2015-12-10 15:39:17'),(154,'TUMULT','tumult','A component of the [QUANTUM](/quantumtheory) system that deals with [layer 2](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/OSI_model) data.','Little is known about this program. Robert Sesek hypothesizes that TUMULT is a hardware device that splits off network traffic for processing by [TURMOIL](/turmoil).','2015-01-15 04:58:06','2015-07-25 19:37:55'),(155,'TUNING FORK','tuning-fork','An unknown tool from the [ANT implant catalog](http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/NSA_ANT_catalog).','The only known mention of this tool is in the concept of operations diagram for [WISTFULTOLL](/wistfulltoll).','2015-01-15 04:58:16','2015-12-10 15:48:48'),(156,'TURBINE','turbine','A command and control (C&C) system for software implants.','The C&C system sends operator commands to computers infected with implants such as [STRAITBIZARRE](/straitbizarre).','2015-01-15 04:58:24','2015-07-25 14:59:15'),(157,'TURBOPANDA','turbopanda','A software implant from the [ANT implant catalog](http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/NSA_ANT_catalog) that allows remote monitoring and management of Huawei routers.','This implant allows the operator to read and write arbitrary memory on the device, execute arbitrary code, or execute the contents of a network packet. Persistence is provided by the [HALLUXWATER](/halluxwater) implant.\n\nThis is a joint NSA/CIA program.','2015-01-15 04:58:29','2015-12-09 05:11:53'),(158,'TURBULENCE','turbulence','An umbrella program that aims to search all global communications online.','This program replaces the defunct [TRAILBLAZER](/trailblazer) and was launched in 2005. Like its predecessor, TRAILBLAZER is intended to monitor and record online communications. Going a step farther, it also intends to disrupt adversaries\' communications capabilities online.\n\nGeneral Alexander (then the director of the NSA) wrote that turbulence was *the most important program in the agency.*\n\nIt was briefly the subject of media scrutiny in 2007 for being a notorious boondoggle: at a cost of $500M per year, the program was reportedly struggling to work correctly and was producing dismal results. The cumulative cost of the project exceeded $2B.\n\nNotably, the NSA\'s authority to authorize new programs had been curtailed by congress in 2004. Therefore, the NSA funded TRAILBLAZER by reallocating funds from other projects, leading some congressional representative to reprimand the agency, albeit in a classified annex to an appropriations bills.','2015-01-15 04:59:07','2015-07-21 04:21:15'),(159,'TURMOIL','turmoil','A high-speed, passive collection system for intercepting foreign satellites, microwave, and cable communications across the globe.','Information is collected from a variety of sources, including, but not limited to:\n\n* [BLARNEY](/blarney)\n* [FAIRVIEW](/fairview)\n* [STORMBREW](/stormbrew)\n* [OAKSTAR](/oakstar)\n* [PRISM](/prism)\n* [FAA](/faa)\n* [RAMPART-A](/rampart-a)\n* [WINDSTOP](/windstop)\n* [RAMPART-I/X](/rampart-i)\n* [MYSTIC](/mystic)\n\nTURMOIL operates at the packet level — not session level — so it can handle some special types of traffic that other collections systems cannot handle.\n\nThe system can handle [VPN](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Virtual_private_network) and [VoIP](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Voice_over_IP) traffic through the [APEX](/apex) system. It can apparently also handle encrypted traffic by interfacing with the [BULLRUN](/bullrun) system.\n\nAlthough TURMOIL itself is a passive collections systems, it can \"tip\" an active collections systems such as [TURBINE](/turbine).','2015-01-15 04:59:17','2015-07-25 14:58:23'),(160,'TUTELAGE','tutelage','A DOD active network defense system.','This is not an NSA program (although it is unclear if the NSA originally developed it). Knowledge of TUTELAGE is declassified but detailed information is apparently still classified. TUTELAGE is known to the public as EINSTEIN-3.\n\nTUTELAGE aims to disrupt the entire adversary development lifecycle, beginning with signals intelligence (via [CYBERQUEST](/cyberquest), [XKEYSCORE](/xkeyscore), [GNOMEVISION](/gnomevision), [POPQUIZ](/popquiz), etc.) to discover and preempt the adversary\'s malware design process.\n\nIn addition to blocking attacks, it can also redirect attacks to [honeypots](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Honeypot_(computing)) for further analysis, substitute benign software for malware, delay attacks. It can also fake a success status to the adversary to create the illusion of a successful attack.\n\nThe system can communicate with unclassified systems such as the DOD\'s [Host-based Security System (HBSS)](http://www.disa.mil/Cybersecurity/Network-Defense/HBSS) by translating classified signatures into less sensitive alert messages.\n\nFinally, TUTELAGE can feed into [QUANTUM](/quantumtheory) to enable offensive use of the captured malware.','2015-01-15 04:59:21','2015-07-25 19:33:33'),(161,'TWISTEDKILT','twistedkilt','A utility for managing a hard drive\'s [Host Protected Area (HPA)](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Host_protected_area).','This utility hides a software implant in the normally-invisible HPA of a hard drive. Used in conjunction with a [BIOS](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/BIOS) flashing utility like [ARKSTREAM](/arkstream), TWISTEDKILT also maintains persistence by periodically re-installing the implant.','2015-01-15 04:59:25','2015-12-08 22:20:50'),(162,'TYPHON HX','typhon-hx','TYPHON HX is a \"network-in-a-box\" from the [ANT implant catalog](http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/NSA_ANT_catalog) that is used for setting up a cellular phone network.','The macro-class Typhon is a Network-In-a-Box (NIB), which includes all the necessary architecture to support Mobile Station call processing and SMS messaging in a stand-alone chassis with a pre-provisioning capability. Typhon supports [GSM](http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/GSM) bands 850/900/1800/1900 and associated full GSM signaling and call control.\n\nOperators are able to geolocate registered handsets when they register with the Typhon unit. Tactical SIGINT elements use this equipment to find, fix and finish targeted handset users.\n\nThe Typhon system kit includes the amplified Typhon system, OAM&P Laptop, cables, antennas and AD/DC power supply. An 800 WH LiIon Battery kit is offered separately. A bracket and mounting kit are available upon request.\n\n*Unit Cost:* N/A','2015-01-15 04:59:32','2015-01-18 03:40:47'),(163,'UNITEDRAKE','unitedrake','An trojan for computers running Microsoft Windows.','This trojan supplants [VALIDATOR](/validator) and [OLYMPUSFIRE](/olympusfire) and is more sophisticated than its predecessors. It has a plugin architecture so that its capabilities can be extended over time. Known plugins include [CAPTIVATEDAUDIENCE](/captivatedaudience), [GUMFISH](/gumfish), [FOGGYBOTTOM](/foggybottom), and [GROK](/grok). Combined, these plugins give UNITEDRAKE vast power to monitor a target\'s activities on a computer, including keystrokes, browsing history, files, microphone, video camera, etc.','2015-01-15 04:59:38','2015-07-25 20:27:29'),(164,'VAGRANT','vagrant','A [SIGAD](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/SIGINT_Activity_Designator) that designates signals collected from computer screens.','Not much is known about this SIGAD. Presumably it refers to implants such as [RAGEMASTER](/ragemaster).','2015-01-15 04:59:43','2015-12-09 00:45:27'),(165,'VALIDATOR','validator','A \"stage 1\" software implant that provides back door access to computers running some versions of Windows.','As part of the [FOXACID](/foxacid) exploitation system, this trojan provides backdoor access to a targeted system. The trojan occasionally contacts an agency listening post (LP) to receive queued tasks from it. The trojan executes the requested tasks and sends back the results.\n\nPossible tasks include:\n\n* Put a file on the target computer.\n* Get a file from the target computer.\n* Run a program.\n* Get system information.\n* Uninstall itself.\n\nThis appears to be a more primitive implant, superceded by more sophisticated alternatives like [OLYMPUSFIRE](/olympusfire) and [UNITEDRAKE](/unitedrake). VALIDATOR is still used as a first stage in order to load the more advanced implants before uninstalling itself.','2015-01-15 04:59:51','2015-12-09 02:02:18'),(166,'VIEWPLATE','viewplate','A processing system in the [ANT implant catalog](http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/NSA_ANT_catalog)  that decodes a baseband video signal from [PHOTOANGLO](/photoanglo).','Little is known about this system.','2015-01-15 04:59:55','2015-12-09 05:54:28'),(167,'WAGONBED','wagonbed','A hardware implant from the [ANT implant catalog](http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/NSA_ANT_catalog) that enables covert wireless communications.','WAGONBED enables covert radio frequency (RF)  communications to and from servers that are air gapped. It interfaces to the host computer via [I2C](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/I%C2%B2C). It used in conjunction with [CROSSBEAM](/crossbeam) for data exfiltration or with [IRONCHEF](/ironchef) for remote software implant management. \n\nIt supports the  HP Proliant 380DL G5 server. It is typically installed via supply chain interdiction.','2015-01-15 04:59:59','2015-12-08 22:52:17'),(168,'WATERWITCH','waterwitch','WATERWITCH is an implant from the [ANT implant catalog](http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/NSA_ANT_catalog) used for locating a nearby (<1 mile) mobile handset.','WATERWITCH is a hand-held \"finishing tool\" – meaning that it is used for locating adversaries for elimination – that geolocates targeted handsets in the field.\n\nTactical Operators use WATERWITCH to locate handsets (last mile) where handset is connected to Typhon or similar equipment interrogator. WATERWITCH emits tone and gives signal strength of target handset. Directional antenna on unit allows operator to locate specific handset.\n\n#### Features\n\n* Split display/controller for flexible deployment capability\n* External antenna for DFing target; internal antenna for communication with active interrogator\n* Multiple technology capability based on SDR Platform; currently UMTS, with GSM and CDMA2000 under development\n* Approximate size 3\" x 7.5\" x 1.25\" (radio), 2.5\" x 5\" x 0.75\" (display); radio shrink in planning stages\n* Display uses E-Ink technology for low light emissions\n\n*Unit Cost:* N/A','2015-01-15 05:00:04','2015-01-17 04:45:15'),(169,'WHITETAMALE','whitetamale','A collections program focused on the Mexican Public Security Secretariat (SSP).','This program gathers intelligence on drug trafficking, human trafficking, and general border security issues in Mexico. It targets system administrators and telecom engineers.','2015-01-15 05:00:08','2015-12-09 02:48:33'),(170,'WISTFULTOLL','wistfultoll','WISTFULLTOLL is a software program from the [ANT implant catalog](http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/NSA_ANT_catalog) used for harvesting forensic data from Windows PCs.','WISTFULTOLL is a [UNITEDRAKE](/unitedrake) and [STRAITBIZZARE](/straitbizarre) plug-in used for harvesting and returning forensic information from a target using Windows Management Instrumentation (WMI) calls and Registry extractions.\n\nThis plug-in supports systems running Microsoft Windows 2000, 2003, and XP.\n\nThrough remote access or interdiction, WISTFULLTOLL is executed as either a UNITEDRAKE or STRAITBAZZARE plug-in or as a stand-alone executable. If used remotely, the extracted information is sent back to NSA through UNITEDRAKE or STRAITBIZZARE. Execution via interdiction may be accomplished by non-technical operator through use of a USB thumb drive, where extracted information will be saved to that thumb drive.\n\n*Unit Cost:* $0','2015-01-15 05:00:14','2015-01-17 22:46:19'),(171,'YELLOWPIN','yellowpin','A very small, embedded computer from the [ANT implant catalog](http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/NSA_ANT_catalog).','The details of this embedded computer are unknown. Its only mention is in the ANT catalog entry for [HOWLERMONKEY](/howlermonkey). This computer is paired with an RF device, such as HOWLERMONKEY, to create a complete implant.','2015-01-15 05:00:21','2015-12-10 15:51:27'),(172,'ZESTYLEAK','zestyleak','A software implant from the [ANT implant catalog](http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/NSA_ANT_catalog) that targets routers.','The exact capabilities of this implant are unknown. Presumably, it enables remote management of the router as well as data exfiltration.\n\nZESTYLEAK is persisted using a firmware implant such as [FEEDTROUGH](/feedtrough). It is similar to [BANANAGLEE](/bananaglee).','2015-01-15 05:00:27','2015-12-09 00:16:14'),(173,'XKEYSCORE','xkeyscore','XKEYSCORE is a computer network exploitation (CNE) system for monitoring, \"nearly everything a user does on the internet,\" and it specifically targets privacy-conscious users.','Also known as XKS, this program targets users of online privacy tools, such as [Tor](https://www.torproject.org/) and [Tails](https://tails.boum.org/). For example, one of the program\'s targets is a Tor server at the University of Erlangen in Germany. XKEYSCORE monitors Tor servers such as this one, as well as all users who connect to them.\n\nThe original version of XKS depended on another collections system called [WEALTHYCLUSTER](/wealthycluster), which was ultimately not scalable enough.\n\nThe second generation of XKS utilized the [TURMOIL](/turmoil) passive collections system, which provides much better scalability than WEALTHYCLUSTER. Only 5% of TURMOIL data is forwarded to XKEYSCORE, determined based on selectors such as email address, keyword, subnet, domain, or technology (e.g. [Tor](https://www.torproject.org/)).\n\nThe third generation collections system comes from a system called [Deep Dive](/deep-dive), which provides very fast sessionization and filtering of internet traffic.','2015-01-15 05:11:48','2015-07-25 15:28:41'),(174,'Find/Fix/Finish','find-fix-finish','Find/Fix/Finish is intelligence lingo for the process of locating and removing adversaries. It is not a codename for a specific project, per se.','*Find:* Discover the current location of an adversary.\n\n*Fix:* Ensure that the adversary stays in a fixed location.\n\n*Finish:* Eliminate the adversary, either by capture or by killing.','2015-01-17 00:16:59','2015-01-17 00:25:18'),(177,'TRAILBLAZER','trailblazer','A defunct program for recording and monitor all global communications online.','TRAILBLAZER was one of two competing systems (the other being [ThinThread](/thinthread)] that aimed to monitor all global digital communications for national security interests.\n\nDue to (rather ironic) privacy concerns with ThinThread, NSA Director Michael Hayden canceled the ThinThread program and poured resources into TRAILBLAZER instead. Despite the overwhelming management and financial support, however, TRAILBLAZER was abandoned in 2006 as a failed project — a $1.2 boondoggle. SAIC, the lead contractor on the project, reaped a windfall: awarded $280M in 2002 to begin working on TRAILBLAZER.\n\nThe rapid demise of the program was due, at least in part, to a scathing inspector general (IG) report that dressed down agency leaders for incompetent oversight. That IG report was marked secret (but unclassified), making it illegal to release it to the American public. [Thomas Drake](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Thomas_Andrews_Drake), an NSA insider and critic of TRAILBLAZER, leaked the secret report to the Baltimore Sun. Drake was later indicted under the [Espionage Act](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Espionage_Act_of_1917) for his actions.','2015-07-21 04:07:53','2015-07-21 05:10:02'),(179,'Wealthy Cluster','wealthy-cluster','A program that combines human intelligence with online resources to track down terrorists.','This is a small scale program related to the much larger [TURBULENCE](/turbulence) project. This program reportedly led to the capture of multiple members of Al-Qaeda.','2015-07-21 04:14:14','2015-07-21 04:17:42'),(180,'ThinThread','thinthread','A defunct program to monitor all global, online communications.','ThinThread was one of two competing programs at the agency (the other being [TRAILBLAZER](/trailblazer)) circa 2000 that aimed to monitor all global, digital communications. The program was championed by a well known cryptographer/mathematician that worked at the agency, [Bill Binney](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/William_Binney_(U.S._intelligence_official)).\n\nDesigned to address the growing problem of ever increasing data sizes, ThinThread eschewed centralized archival and data retention, instead opting for distributed and instant analysis of data. Needless data was discarded on the spot. The data was scalable to accomodate increasing amounts of data; it was also extensible to to incorporate new types of information that might be useful to an intelligence analyst.\n\n> As Binney imagined it, ThinThread would correlate data from financial transactions, travel records, Web searches, G.P.S. equipment, and any other “attributes” that an analyst might find useful in pinpointing “the bad guys.” \n\nThinThread was reportedly very successful in early testing. In fact, due to very aggressive reaping of digital data, the system\'s designers built in privacy and minimization features in order to protect the 4th amendment rights of U.S. citizens who\'s data was unexpectedly caught up in the system.\n\nBill Binney believed that ThinThread may have been able to prevent the 9/11 attacks, if the system had been put into operation soon enough. He also later apologized to the American people, believing that ThinThread had been misused against American citizens.\n\n> I should apologize to the American people. It’s violated everyone’s rights. It can be used to eavesdrop on the whole world.\n\nThinThread was ultimately rejected due to agency lawyers\' privacy concerns prior to 9/11, prompting NSA Director Michael Hayden to move forward with TRAILBLAZER instead, despite the latter being far more expensive and less effective than ThinThread.\n\nAnother supporter of ThinThread, named [Thomas Drake](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Thomas_Andrews_Drake), was later indicted under the [Espionage Act](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Espionage_Act_of_1917) for leaking information challenging TRAILBLAZER and supporting ThinThread.','2015-07-21 04:24:02','2015-07-21 05:06:15'),(181,'Jackpot','jackpot','A program for finding and fixing bugs in agency software.','Mentioned only briefly in a New Yorker interview by [Thomas Drake](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Thomas_Andrews_Drake), Jackpot is described as, \"focussed on finding and fixing weaknesses in the agency’s software programs.\"','2015-07-21 04:38:41','2015-07-21 04:41:30'),(182,'FELONYCROWBAR','felonycrowbar','A configuration tool for [STRAITBIZARRE](/straitbizarre).','This graphical ([GUI](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Graphical_user_interface)) configuration tool is used to configure a STRAITBIZARRE implant by selecting which modules to include. FELONYCROWBAR builds a new implant with the selected modules into a ZIP file. An operator can then deploy that ZIP file to a [QUANTUM](/quantumtheory) shooter.','2015-07-24 04:13:43','2015-07-24 04:23:15'),(183,'FORESTPLACE','forestplace','A covert architecture used for deploying software implants.','Not much is known about FORESTPLACE. It is associated with the [FREEFLOW](/.freeflow) project and [ROC](/roc)/[MIT](/mit) covert infrastructure.','2015-07-24 04:31:21','2015-07-24 04:47:59'),(184,'ROC','roc','Remote operations center.','Not a codename but an acronym. The ROC is a group within [Tailored Access Operations (TAO)](/tao) that manages computer implants: embedding them, monitoring them, and collecting data from them. The group has roughly 600 employees spread out over multiple geographic locations.\n\nTheir motto is:\n\n> Your data is our data, your equipment is our equipment - anytime, any place, by any legal means.','2015-07-24 04:33:33','2015-07-24 04:41:38'),(185,'MIT','mit','Mission infrastructure technologies.','A group in [TAO](/tao) that manages the IT infrastructure.','2015-07-24 04:36:59','2015-07-24 04:46:19'),(186,'TAO','tao','Tailored access operations.','The agency\'s elite group of hackers, specialized in infiltrating computers and computer networks.','2015-07-24 04:41:44','2015-07-24 04:42:49'),(187,'QUANTUMSQUIRREL','quantumsquirrel','A technology that allows [TAO](/tao) to masquerade as any IPv4 or IPv6 host.','Not much is known about this technology. It allows the agency to fake traffic in order to make it appear to come from some other location on the internet.','2015-07-24 04:43:28','2015-07-24 04:50:43'),(188,'FUSSYKEEL','fussykeel','A covert architecture used for deploying software implants.','Not much is known about FUSSYKEEL. It is associated with the [FREEFLOW](/.freeflow) project and [ROC](/roc)/[MIT](/mit) covert infrastructure.','2015-07-24 04:51:12','2015-12-10 15:54:24'),(189,'FINGERGNOME','fingergnome','A technology for high-to-low data transfer.','Not much is known about this codename. It is a thread in the [FREEFLOW](/freeflow) project. A version 2.0 exists, which is associated with the [FROZENEARTH](/frozenearth) covert infrastructure.','2015-07-24 04:53:02','2015-07-24 05:00:07'),(190,'FROZENEARTH','frozenearth','A covert infrastructure.','Not much is known about this codename. It is related to the [FREEFLOW](/freeflow) project.','2015-07-24 05:00:20','2015-07-24 05:01:31'),(191,'GENIE NCC','genie-ncc','[GENIE](/genie) Network Configuration Center tool.','This tool manages [CHIMNEYPOOL](/chimneypool) communications links for [STRAITBIZARRE](/straitbizarre) implants via [MIDDLEMAN](/middleman).\n\nThe NCC can be used to create configuration files for CHIMNEYPOOL communications links called [Deployed Node Documents (DND)](/dnd).','2015-07-24 05:11:41','2015-07-24 05:15:09'),(192,'DND','dnd','Deployed Node Document','Not a codename but an acronym. A Deployed Node Document is an XML configuration file for a [CHIMNEYPOOL](/chimneypool) node\'s communications links.','2015-07-24 05:15:18','2015-07-24 05:17:12'),(193,'HANGARSURPLUS','hangarsurplus','A low-to-high [data diode](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Unidirectional_network).','Not much is known about this product. It is used for restricting traffic between \"high\" (i.e. classified) networks and \"low\" (i.e. sensitive but unclassified).','2015-07-24 05:18:59','2015-07-24 05:21:49'),(194,'WSG','wsg','Web Sniper Gateway','Not a codename but an acronym. Not much is known about it. A WSG sits between [MIDDLEMAN](/middleman) and [QUANTUM shooters](/quantumtheory).','2015-07-24 05:25:35','2015-07-24 05:27:08'),(195,'RAMPART-A','rampart-a','A collections system for long-haul internet communications, such as fiber optic runs operated by telecommunications companies.','The system is based on partnerships with communications companies from around the world and provides access to 3 terabits of data per second. Internet data from every single country on the planet is visible at least one RAMPART-A collection point. It is part of the [TURMOIL](/turmoil) collection program.','2015-07-24 05:50:25','2015-07-24 05:56:00'),(196,'RAMPART-T','rampart-t','Signal collection on over land telecommunications cables.','Not much is known about this program.','2015-07-24 05:53:46','2015-07-24 05:55:07'),(197,'RAMPART-M','rampart-m','Signal collection on underseas telecommunications cables.','Not much is known about this program.','2015-07-24 05:53:54','2015-07-24 05:55:26'),(198,'BLARNEY','blarney','A corporate collections program in the [TURMOIL](/turmoil) project.','Not much is known about this collections program.','2015-07-24 05:58:43','2015-07-24 06:17:47'),(199,'STORMBREW','stormbrew','A corporate collections program in the [TURMOIL](/turmoil) project.','Not much is known about this collections program.','2015-07-24 05:59:02','2015-07-24 06:17:57'),(200,'OAKSTAR','oakstar','A corporate collections program in the [TURMOIL](/turmoil) project.','Not much is known about this collections program.','2015-07-24 05:59:29','2015-07-24 06:18:01'),(201,'PRISM','prism','A corporate collections program in the [TURMOIL](/turmoil) project.','Not much is known about this collections program.','2015-07-24 05:59:45','2015-07-24 06:18:05'),(202,'FAA','faa','A corporate collections program in the [TURMOIL](/turmoil) project.','Not much is known about this collections program.','2015-07-24 05:59:53','2015-07-24 06:18:10'),(203,'WINDSTOP','windstop','A foreign collections program in the [TURMOIL](/turmoil) project.','This is a joint collection program between the NSA and [GCHQ](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Government_Communications_Headquarters). It includes multiple collection systems, such as [MUSCULAR](/muscular) and [INCENSER](/incenser).\n\nBy collecting data from a second part (GCHQ), the agency sidesteps regulations regarding collecting data on American citizens.','2015-07-24 06:00:23','2015-07-25 14:10:15'),(204,'RAMPART I/X','rampart-i-x','A unilateral collections program in the [TURMOIL](/turmoil) project.','Not much is known about this collections program.','2015-07-24 06:00:40','2015-07-24 06:31:21'),(205,'MYSTIC','mystic','A unilateral collections program in the [TURMOIL](/turmoil) project targeting phone call data and/or metadata in multiple foreign countries.','Created in 2009 and operational in 2011, this program collects phone calls from several countries, including the Bahamas, Mexico, the Philippines, Kenya, and possibly Iraq and Afghanistan. The total population covered by the program exceeds 250 million people.\n\nThe system nominally focuses on cellular phone call metadata from Mexico, Kenya, and the Philippines, but some subprograms obtain full call data, such as [SOMALGET](/somalget) in the Bahamas. The Intercept has evidence of another country being targeted by MYSTIC for full phone call collection but redacted the name due to security concerns.\n\nThe MYSTIC equipment is installed in telecommunications facilities with the consent of those providers. The agency describes it as:\n\n> MYSTIC is an SSO program for embedded collection systems overtly installed on target networks, predominantly for the collection and processing of wireless/mobile communications networks. The overt purpose is for legitimate commercial services for the Telco\'s themselves; our covert mission is the provision of SIGINT.\n\nThe \"commercial services\" probably refer to lawful interception requests that telecommunications providers are required to support in many countries. (In the US, for example, telcos must comply with [CALEA](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Communications_Assistance_for_Law_Enforcement_Act).) These providers are apparently unaware that the system is also used for warrantless collection.\n\nPhone call data ages out of the system after 30 days. When a target is identified, an analyst can review all phone calls made or received by the target in the last month.','2015-07-24 06:00:55','2015-07-25 19:59:59'),(206,'MUSCULAR','muscular','A corporate collections facility in the [WINDSTOP](/windstop) project that collects data from Google and Yahoo datacenters.','This collections program intercepts data by tapping into the networks that link corporate data centers together. In particular, this program intercepts bulk data being transferred from one Google facility to another. It also collects from Yahoo facilities.\n\nDue to the bulk nature of MUSCULAR, it collects a surprising amount of data. Between December 2012 and January 2013, it collected 181 million records.\n\nData is collected at an access point known as DS-200B, located in England.','2015-07-24 06:01:23','2015-07-25 14:17:25'),(207,'INCENSER','incenser','A corporate collections facility in the [WINDSTOP](/windstop) program.','This facility collects data from a British company called [Cable & Wireless](http://www.cwc.com/) (codenamed [GERONTIC](/gerontic)) that offers mobile phone and high-speed internet services. \n\nIt collects 14 billion pieces of data per month.','2015-07-24 06:01:50','2015-07-25 20:37:44'),(208,'PINWALE','pinwale','A storage system and search engine for intercepted text, such as chat and e-mail transcripts.','This system is supposed to have safeguards in place for not collecting text data from U.S. citizens, but has had some major lapses publicly reported. Most notably, PINWALE recorded President Bill Clinton\'s personal emails in 2009.','2015-07-24 06:20:58','2015-07-24 06:29:39'),(209,'DNI','dni','Digital Network Intelligence','Not a codename but an acronym. \"Digital network intelligence\" refers to signals intelligence collected from computer networks, principally the internet.','2015-07-24 06:26:48','2015-07-24 06:27:46'),(210,'BOUNDLESSINFORMANT','boundlessinformant','A data analysis and visualization tool that aggregates signals collection activities from around the world and throughout the agencies numerous programs and authorities.','This tool helps program managers understand what types of signals are being collected in various parts of the world. It can be used to answer specific questions about how much coverage is available in a specific country, or to compare how much raw data is captured by two different sources (a.k.a. SIGADs). It also includes time series data to monitor how much data is ingested each day and to spot trends in signals collection.\n\nThe system uses open source technologies for distributed computing in order to process such a large data set, including [Hadoop](https://hadoop.apache.org/) and [Cloudbase](http://cloudbase.sourceforge.net/).\n\nIn 2013, this tool tracked 97 _billion_ pieces of information from 507 unique SIGADs.','2015-07-24 06:33:43','2015-12-09 00:41:18'),(211,'GERONTIC','gerontic','A British telecommunications firm named [Cable & Wireless](http://www.cwc.com/).','The mobile phone and internet service provider provides data to the NSA and GCHQ as part of the [INCENSER](/incenser) program.','2015-07-25 14:23:08','2015-07-25 14:24:45'),(212,'APEX','apex','A collections system for [VPN](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Virtual_private_network) and [VoIP](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Voice_over_IP) data.','APEX integrates a number of other systems to record and monitor VPN and VoIP traffic on the internet, such as [HAMMERSTEIN](/hammerstein) and [TOYGRIPPE](/toygrippe).','2015-07-25 14:31:51','2015-07-25 14:34:40'),(213,'HAMMERSTEIN','hammerstein','A system that identifies VPN traffic on the internet and forwards it to [TOYGRIPPE](/toygrippe).','Not much is known about this program.','2015-07-25 14:34:52','2015-07-25 14:37:54'),(214,'TOYGRIPPE','toygrippe','A database of VPN endpoints that is used for determining if identifiable VPN traffic should be recorded and/or further analyzed.','Not much is known about this program.','2015-07-25 14:34:58','2015-07-25 18:38:52'),(215,'KEYCARD','keycard','A database of IP addresses flagged for content targeting.','Not much is known about this program. It is used by the [TURMOIL](/turmoil) program.','2015-07-25 14:39:22','2015-07-25 14:40:45'),(216,'BULLRUN','bullrun','A program that aims to defeat or undermine encryption by collaborating with the technology industry.','One of the most expensive programs at the agency, BULLRUN costs $250 million per year. It aims to attack a number of mainstream encryption technologies and technology companies.\n\nThe Guardian writes:\n\n> \"Project Bullrun deals with NSA\'s abilities to defeat the encryption used in specific network communication technologies. Bullrun involves multiple sources, all of which are extremely sensitive.\" The document reveals that the agency has capabilities against widely used online protocols, such as HTTPS, voice-over-IP and Secure Sockets Layer (SSL), used to protect online shopping and banking.\n\nNone of the companies collaborating with the NSA are named in the documents released by The Guardian.\n\nIn some cases, the NSA intentionally inserts weaknesses or vulnerabilities into products brought to them by the private sector. The NSA\'s [Commercial Solutions Center](https://www.nsa.gov/business/programs/ncsc.shtml) is ostensibly an arm of the agency that helps corporations assess the security of their products, and also find introductions to prospective government buyers. As part of BULLRUN, the Commercial Solutions Center also abused these intimate relationships with corporations to deliberately insert flaws into their products in a way that would be undetectable to the average end user, or even most nation state actors.\n\nThe Guardian:\n\n> It is used by the NSA to \"to leverage sensitive, co-operative relationships with specific industry partners\" to insert vulnerabilities into security products. Operatives were warned that this information must be kept top secret \"at a minimum\".\n> \n> A more general NSA classification guide reveals more detail on the agency\'s deep partnerships with industry, and its ability to modify products. It cautions analysts that two facts must remain top secret: that NSA makes modifications to commercial encryption software and devices \"to make them exploitable\", and that NSA \"obtains cryptographic details of commercial cryptographic information security systems through industry relationships\".\n\nThe NSA cooperates greatly with GCHQ in this task, who have their own equivalent program under the moniker EDGEHILL.','2015-07-25 14:41:46','2015-12-10 16:09:08'),(217,'HAMMERCHANT','hammerchant','A [TURMOIL](/turmoil) plugin that processes [VoIP](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Voice_over_IP) traffic on the internet.','This plugin allows VoIP data to be process liked like regular [PSTN](/pstn) phone calls by processing the data through [CONVEYANCE](/conveyance) and storing it in [NUCLEON](/nucleon) for analysts to listen to.','2015-07-25 14:43:03','2015-07-25 14:45:32'),(218,'CONVEYANCE','conveyance','A system for processing phone call data for long-term storage.','This system can take in phone call data from both [PSTN](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Public_switched_telephone_network) and [VoIP](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Voice_over_IP) sources. It processes the data to prepare it for storage in [NUCLEON](/nucleon).','2015-07-25 14:43:16','2015-07-25 14:49:28'),(219,'NUCLEON','nucleon','A database of phone call data.','Not much is known about this system. It is apparently designed to hold spoken word data.','2015-07-25 14:43:27','2015-07-25 14:50:53'),(220,'FASHIONCLEFT','fashioncleft','A protocol for for packaging data for infiltration and delivering it to an agency listening post (LP).','Not much is known about this protocol.','2015-07-25 15:01:17','2015-07-25 15:03:02'),(221,'TRAFFICTHIEF','trafficthief','A database that contains internet traffic metadata for \"strong-selectors\".','As opposed to [MARINA](/marina), which collects vast volumes of internet traffic metadata, the TRAFFICTHIEF database focuses on a smaller subset of users, presumably those targeted for exploitation through the [QUANTUM](/quantumtheory) program.','2015-07-25 15:01:19','2015-07-25 15:14:22'),(222,'MARINA','marina','A database for metadata about captured internet traffic.','This database holds metadata about users and what they are doing on the internet, captured from a number of upstream programs. It allows analysts to build a pattern-of-life summary for a target.\n\nIt stores 365 days worth of [DNI](/dni) metadata. The database does not have built-in minimization procedures. If data about Americans is accidentally collected, it will continue to reside in MARINA for 365 days.\n\nInformation collected in MARINA can be used for targeting purposes, e.g. with [QUANTUMTHEORY](/quantumtheory).','2015-07-25 15:06:59','2015-12-09 03:24:41'),(223,'WEALTHYCLUSTER','wealthycluster','A collections system for internet data.','This collections system monitors internet traffic and sessionizes it for feeding into downstream systems, such as [XKEYSCORE](/xkeyscore).','2015-07-25 15:16:32','2015-07-25 15:18:08'),(224,'Deep Dive','deep-dive','A high-performance collections system for internet data.','This high-performance collections system can sessionize internet traffic at 10 gigabits per second (i.e., line speed). It feeds data into the [XKEYSCORE](/xkeyscore) system.','2015-07-25 15:21:26','2015-07-25 15:26:54'),(227,'GENESIS (Language)','genesis-language','A technical language used in the [XKEYSCORE](/xkeyscore) system for determining what internet traffic to capture.','The GENESIS language is used to instruct [Deep Dive](/deep-dive) and [XKEYSCORE](/xkeyscore) what internet traffic to capture and store.\n\nAn example of GENESIS rules targeting [Tor](https://www.torproject.org/) users can be [found here](http://daserste.ndr.de/panorama/xkeyscorerules100.txt).','2015-07-25 15:23:53','2015-07-25 15:30:37'),(228,'LOPERS','lopers','A system for filtering telephony data from cable taps.','Not much is known about this system. Data extracted by LOPERS is sent to [FASCIA](/fascia) for storage and analysis.','2015-07-25 18:12:33','2015-07-25 18:15:02'),(229,'FASCIA','fascia','A database that holds cell phone metadata.','This database contains cell phone metadata, including IMEI and IMSI numbers.','2015-07-25 18:15:12','2015-07-25 18:16:07'),(230,'TWISTEDPATH','twistedpath','A database that contains intelligence of an unknown character.','Little is known about this program. It is believed to contain some type of internet routing metadata.','2015-07-25 18:16:31','2015-07-25 19:31:48'),(231,'TREASUREMAP','treasuremap','A project to map out the entire internet.','The goal of this ambitious project is:\n\n> Map the entire Internet — Any device, anywhere, all the time.\n\nMapping the internet improves both defensive and offensive capabilities, similar to knowing the terrain of a battlefield. It combines data from many sources, including open source intelligence (OSINT), commercial intelligence (COMINT), and the agency\'s own signals intelligence (SIGINT). The system takes in 30 gigabytes of data per day.\n\nIt utilizes protocols such as [BGP](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Border_Gateway_Protocol). Data about BGP is acquire from open sources like [RIPE](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/R%C3%A9seaux_IP_Europ%C3%A9ens_Network_Coordination_Centre) and [APNIC](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Asia-Pacific_Network_Information_Centre) and commercial sources such as Akamai, [SOCIALSTAMP](/socialstamp), and [SEASIDEFERRY](/seasideferry).\n\nIt also utilizes the well-known `traceroute` Unix program the available routes between two points on the internet. It takes in 16-18 million traceroutes per day through a program called [PACKAGEDGOODS](/packagedgoods).\n\nThe agency\'s internal sources feeding into TREASUREMAP are:\n\n* [PACKAGEDGOODS](/packagedgoods)\n* [BLACKPEARL](/blackpearl)\n* [LEAKYFAUCET](/leakyfaucet)\n* [HYDROCASTLE](/hydrocastle)\n* [MASTERSHAKE](/mastershake)\n* [S-TRICKLER](/s-trickler)\n* [TOYGRIPPE](/toygrippe)\n* [DISCOROUTE](/discoroute)\n* [VITALAIR2](/vitalair2)\n* [IPGeoTrap](/ipgeotrap)\n* [JOLLYROGER](/jollyroger)\n* [TUTELAGE](/tutelage)\n\nThe system fully supports IPv4 and has limited support for IPv6. It claims to focus on \"logical layers (router and autonomous system)\" but also operates at physical (layer 1), data (layer 2), and application (layer 7).\n\nTREASUREMAP sports a user interface for searching and visualizing the data in the following ways:\n\n* IP address\n* Router\n* DNS\n* MAC address\n* IP subnet/prefix (CIDR notation)\n* Registry netblock\n* SIGAD or Case Notation\n* Autonomous System (AS) Number\n* Free Text\n\nThe system is developed in 90 day sprints and contains a built-in feedback mechanism for analysts to provide requests back to the development team.','2015-07-25 18:17:09','2015-07-25 18:34:41'),(232,'PACKAGEDGOODS','packagedgoods','A clandestine `traceroute` and DNS processor.','This system collects `traceroute` data on the public internet from 700 public \"traceroute\" servers as well as 13 clandestine servers installed in data centers around the globe. The system pulls about 4,000 traceroutes per day from the public servers, and 16.5 million traceroutes per day from the clandestine servers.','2015-07-25 18:35:12','2015-07-25 18:46:14'),(233,'LEAKYFAUCET','leakyfaucet','A database of 802.11 WiFi IP addresses and clients collected from [STUN](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/STUN) data.','Little is known about this program.','2015-07-25 18:35:30','2015-07-25 18:49:49'),(234,'HYDROCASTLE','hydrocastle','A database of 802.11 WiFi configuration data.','Little is known about this program. The data contained in the database is obtained via [CNE](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Computer_network_operations).','2015-07-25 18:35:51','2015-07-25 18:51:25'),(235,'MASTERSHAKE','mastershake','A database of [FORNSAT](/fornsat) and WiFi collection data.','Little is known about this program.','2015-07-25 18:36:05','2015-07-25 18:53:05'),(236,'S-TRICKLER','s-trickler','A database of IP address fingerprints and potential vulnerabilities.','Little is known about this database. The data is collected from [FORNSAT](/fornsat).','2015-07-25 18:36:20','2015-07-25 19:26:11'),(237,'DISCOROUTE','discoroute','A database of router configuration files.','Little is known about this program. The data is collected from [CNE](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Computer_network_operations) as well as passive signals intelligence (presumably [TURMOIL](/turmoil)).','2015-07-25 18:36:51','2015-07-25 19:28:21'),(238,'VITALAIR2','vitalair2','A system that scans IP addresses for vulnerabilities that [TAO](/tao) has exploits for.','Little is known about this program.','2015-07-25 18:37:05','2015-07-25 19:28:51'),(239,'IPGeoTrap','ipgeotrap','A geolocation service for IP addresses.','Little is known about this program.','2015-07-25 18:37:23','2015-07-25 19:29:06'),(240,'JOLLYROGER','jollyroger','A database of network environment metadata about computers exploited by [TAO](/tao).','Little is known about this program.','2015-07-25 18:37:33','2015-07-25 19:29:37'),(241,'FORNSAT','fornsat','A collections system for foreign satellite communications.','This program is based at Menwith Hill station in the UK. It uses large antennae housed inside geodesic domes.','2015-07-25 18:53:14','2017-02-09 15:48:37'),(242,'SOMALGET','somalget','A program to record and archive all cell phone calls in the Bahamas.','This program, under the [MYSTIC](/mystic) umbrella, operates without the knowledge or consent of the Bahamian government. The agency apparently obtained access to this data through a partnership with the [DEA](http://www.dea.gov/index.shtml). Presumably, the DEA uses this information to locate drug traffickers operating in the Caribbean.\n\nSOMALGET may also refer to a protected source, a private corporation that provides equipment and/or assistance to the MYSTIC program.','2015-07-25 19:42:54','2015-07-25 20:02:40'),(243,'SpySpace','spyspace','An internal \"social\" network.','Not much is known about this program, except that it is used for disseminating information across the agency.','2015-07-25 20:11:24','2015-07-25 20:12:28'),(244,'CAPTIVATEDAUDIENCE','captivatedaudience','A plugin for the [UNITEDRAKE](/unitedrake) trojan that records audio from a computer\'s microphone.','Little is known about this plugin.','2015-07-25 20:27:50','2015-07-25 20:35:14'),(245,'GUMFISH','gumfish','A plugin for the [UNITEDRAKE](/unitedrake) trojan that records audio and video from a computer\'s webcam.','Little is known about this plugin.','2015-07-25 20:34:01','2015-07-25 20:36:09'),(246,'FOGGYBOTTOM','foggybottom','A plugin for the [UNITEDRAKE](/unitedrake) trojan that exfiltrates browsing history and passwords.','Little is known about this plugin.','2015-07-25 20:34:49','2015-07-25 20:36:32'),(247,'GROK','grok','A plugin for the [UNITEDRAKE](/unitedrake) trojan that records keystrokes.','Little is known about this plugin.','2015-07-25 20:34:57','2015-07-25 20:36:40'),(248,'MAGNETIC','magnetic','A [SIGAD](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/SIGINT_Activity_Designator) that designates signals collected from \"sensor collection of magnetic emanations\".','Not much is known about this SIGAD.','2015-12-09 00:45:51','2015-12-09 00:49:26'),(249,'Byzantine Foothold','byzantine-foothold','A subprogram within [Byzantine Hades](/byzantine-hades).','Little is known about this program.','2015-12-09 01:49:52','2015-12-09 01:52:28'),(250,'ERRONEOUSINGENUITY','erroneousingenuity','An exploit for Firefox versions 13.0-16.0.2.','Also known as \"ERIN\", this exploit was used against [Tor](https://www.torproject.org/) users under the [EGOTISTICALGIRAFFE](/egotisticalgiraffe) program.','2015-12-09 03:32:42','2015-12-09 03:39:43'),(251,'GREAT EXPECTATIONS','great-expectations','A [question focused dataset](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Question-focused_dataset) that attempts to deanonymize Tor users via correlation from dark web to open web.','Based on a GCHQ program with the name EPICFAIL, GREAT EXPECTATIONS attempts to identify users on Tor by correlating their activity on websites when they are not using Tor.','2015-12-09 04:55:11','2015-12-09 04:58:23'),(252,'MAESTRO','maestro','A very small computing platform from the [ANT implant catalog](http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/NSA_ANT_catalog) that is used to implement covert hardware implants.','The details of this predecessor to [MAESTRO-II](/maestro-ii) are not publicly known, but the ANT catalog entry compares the features of MAESTRO and MAESTRO-II, implying that MAESTRO is a single ARM7 core running at 66Mhz with 256KB of on-board SRAM and no flash storage, additional SDRAM, or FPGA. The predecessor to this design used a much less powerful [HC12 microcontroller](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Freescale_68HC12).\n\n*Unit Cost:* Unknown','2015-12-09 15:14:58','2015-12-09 15:21:45'),(253,'MAINWAY','mainway','A [hypthothesized] database for domestic metadata call chaining.','This existence of this program was inferred from analyzing redactions in an NSA document. The word \"MAINWAY\" appears to fit the redacted block perfectly.','2016-01-11 02:59:37','2016-01-11 03:07:20'),(254,'GUNMAN','gunman','A cold war era operation to to detect and remove Russian implants installed inside American office equipment in the Moscow embassy.','In the early 1980\'s, the USA was tipped off by an ally that the USSR had developed an advanced implant suitable for hiding in common office equipment. GUNMAN was an elaborate operation in the early 1980\'s to remove possibly contaminated office equipment from the US embassy in Moscow, replace it with fresh equipment, and analyze the removed equipment for the presence of any implants. Furthermore, the operation need to be performed without the knowledge of the Russians, for fear of tipping them off.\n\nPresident Ronald Reagan approved the operation in 1984. The NSA and Department of State collaborated to replace hundreds of items from the embassy in Moscow and ship the removed devices back to Ft. Meade. The operation focused on cryptographic devices used in the embassy but also included samples of all of other office equipment: copy machines, typewriters, printers, teletypes, computers, etc. The agency had no idea how the implant worked or what equipment it would be buried inside of.\n\nBack at Ft. Meade, a lone engineer working late at night finally discovered the possible existence of an implant in an unlikely place: inside an IBM Selectric II typewriter. As the only employee working that late, he had to wait until the following morning to share his discovery with coworkers; further analysis and reverse engineering confirmed the employee\'s finding. The employee was rewarded with a $5,000 bonus. Additional contaminated typewriters were then removed from the Moscow embassy as well as the Leningrad embassy.\n\nKnowledge of the operation was leaked to CBS in 1985 via an unknown source. The story ran in the evening news on March 25. A top secret report on the project was written and published in the annals of the United States Cryptologic History (a publication of the NSA) in 2009. That report was declassified in 2011, approximately 25 years after the operation concluded.\n\nThe NSA considers GUNMAN to be an extremely important operation for the agency, establishing the agency\'s role within the intelligence community and creating credibility and awareness of its capabilities. The report, with a slightly propagandistic tone, extols the virtues of the NSA being able to overcome bureaucratic hurdles both within and without the agency in order to successfully execute the operation in such a short time.','2016-02-03 04:02:39','2016-02-04 16:26:42'),(255,'PINECONE','pinecone','A [SCIF](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sensitive_Compartmented_Information_Facility) in New Jersey that processes signals intelligence.','This \"centralized processing facility\" collects signals from the [FAIRVIEW](./fairview) program and possibly other programs, too.','2016-02-04 17:14:45','2016-02-04 17:17:51'),(256,'STELLARWIND','stellarwind','A mass surveillance program authorized by President George W. Bush in the wake of the 9/11 attacks.','Also known as [STARBURST](./starburst), this mass surveillance program was nominally aimed at targeting international communications of people with known links to terrorist organizations. In practice, the NSA was authorized to record any communications where one party was believed to be outside the United States. The program collected many different types of communications, including voice, data, and fax transmissions. None of these surveillance activities were conducted with a warrant, raising questions of fourth amendment violations.\n\nThe program was authorized by President George W. Bush in 2002. The program was reviewed every 45 days, and President Bush re-authorized the program at least 30 times during his presidency. Although principally an NSA surveillance program, the FBI and CIA were integral in its operations and also received data from the program.\n\nThe New York Times learned of the program in 2004, but withheld publication before that year\'s presidential election due to [pressure from the White House](http://www.huffingtonpost.com/2014/05/14/james-risen-new-york-times_n_5324303.html). The New York Times finally broke the story in December, 2005, nearly a year after President Bush had won a second term. \n\nThe NYT\'s anonymous source was later revealed to be Thomas Tamm, a former attorney with the Department Of Justice. Tamm, holding a TS-SCI clearance at the time and believing the program to be illegal, blew the whistle. He claims that other DOJ employees concurred that the program was likely illegal. As of 2016, Tamm is still facing [criminal charges and possible disbarment](http://www.usnews.com/news/articles/2016-01-27/pre-snowden-whistleblower-thomas-tamm-faces-misconduct-charges-12-years-later) for his actions in this matter.','2016-03-26 19:27:35','2016-03-26 19:57:20'),(257,'STARBURST','starburst','A mass surveillance program that was later renamed to [STELLARWIND](./stellarwind).','See the entry at [STELLARWIND](./stellarwind).','2016-03-26 19:33:44','2016-03-26 19:34:43'),(258,'FIRSTFRUIT','firstfruit','A database of \"insecurity-related\" records.','The FIRSTFRUIT Foreign Knowledge Database contains records related to breaches of classified information, including:\n\n* espionage damage assessments\n* cryptologic insecurities\n* unauthorized disclosures\n* [demarches](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/D%C3%A9marche)\n* liaison exchanges\n\nAs of 2003, this database contained contained over 5,000 records. This database is maintained by the office of Intelligence Security Issues. This group reviews hundreds of news articles every day looking for potential breaches of classified information and uses internal NSA databases to verify whether published data is classified or not. They also review books and internet articles. Some breaches are forwarded to the NSA\'s Public Affairs Office (PAO) for further work.','2016-06-02 19:19:30','2016-06-02 19:36:40'),(259,'WINTERLIGHT','winterlight','A program within [QUANTUM](/quantumtheory) aiming to hack high-value, foreign computers and networks.','This joint program involved the NSA, GCHQ, and the Swedish FRA. The program seeks to compromise high-value, foreign computers and networks. Sweden\'s intelligence agency became involved due to their, \"unusual technical abilities and reputation for secrecy,\" and also, \"because a large percentage of Russian communications traveled through Sweden.\"','2017-01-24 15:56:43','2017-01-24 16:05:22'),(261,'OVERHEAD','overhead','A collections system that uses satellites to intercept terrestrial wireless communications.','This system uses satellites positioned over countries of interest to intercept terrestrial wireless communications such as cellphone calls and WiFi data.','2017-02-09 15:46:24','2017-02-09 15:49:31'),(262,'MOONPENNY','moonpenny','A satellite surveillance mission based at Menwith Hill.','This system collects data from satellites. As of 2009, it was collecting from 163 satellite links. In a 12 hour period, this system can collect 335 million metadata records. The collected data is very diverse, including phone calls, text messages, and internet data.','2017-02-09 15:49:45','2017-02-09 15:52:24'),(263,'GHOSTHUNTER','ghosthunter','A surveillance tool that locates targets when the \"log onto the internet.\"','This tool is used in capture-kill operations. For example, in 2007, this system identified an Iraqi man named Abu Sayf when he logged into his Yahoo account inside a cafe in the town of Anah. The man was captured two days later.\n\nThis tool has operational bases in the UK, Cyprus, and Japan, enabling almost complete coverage anywhere on the planet.','2017-02-09 15:52:59','2017-02-09 16:00:09'),(264,'GHOSTWOLF','ghostwolf','A capture-kill project that geolocates targets of interest.','This project, based at Menwith Hill, identified capture-kill targets at approximately 40 internet cafes in Yemen.','2017-02-09 16:00:20','2017-02-09 16:06:03');
