INSERT INTO `content` VALUES (1,'about','## Background\n\nAmerican taxpayers shelled out [$10.8 billion in 2013](http://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-srv/special/national/black-budget/) to fund the NSA. This [is more money](http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/2013_United_States_federal_budget) than we spent on the Department Of Commerce ($9B), the Environmental Protection Agency ($8.9B ), or the National Science Foundation ($7.5B). It is _seven times as much_ as we spent on the Small Business Administration ($1.4B)\n\nThe budget for all American intelligence agencies combined surpassed $50 billion in 2013. This figure tops spending on the Department of Housing and Urban Development ($46.3B), the Department of Justice ($36.5B), and the Department Of Energy ($35B).\n\nThe intelligence budget itself was classified information until it was leaked to the public by Edward Snowden. The absurdity of this fact should not be overlooked: the amount of money is such an important national secret that leaking the _budget_ is considered espionage! Imagine how easy it is to escape scrutiny when taxpayers don\'t even know how much of their money you are spending.\n\nThe purpose of this website is to help organize the numerous tidbits of information revealed through these leaks and allow American taxpayers to understand where their money is going. Regardless of your political beliefs about surveillance, public safety, and civil liberties, surely we can all agree that a properly functioning democracy is severely hampered by over-classification. When taxpayers _don\'t even know how much they\'re spending_, how can they possibly have a meaningful say in their government?\n\n## Organization\n\nThis site focuses on the codenames themselves: the names are equal parts _James Bond_ and _Get Smart_. The names are sometimes intriguing, sometimes ominous, and sometimes absurd. The idea of an all-powerful, omnipresent intelligence agency is disturbing, but it also appeals to a curious part of our nature – the part of our nature that wants to believe that the crazy things we see in the movies are actually real.\n\nMany of the codenames evoke vivid imagery. Therefore, this site lets users upload their own artwork to complement and illustrate each of the codenames. Users can vote on which images are best. In this way, we hope to crowd source an incredible collection of artwork to match the incredible data that we now have on these intelligence programs.\n\n## Get Involved\n\nThere are several ways you can get involved with this website:\n\n1. [Browse](/index/a) the site or [search](/search) for topics that interest you. Learn about these programs; educate yourself and others. Spread the word.\n2. Please vote on the artwork and –-- if you fancy yourself an artist -- please upload your own artwork! Other users will be able to vote for the artwork that they like.\n3. We can also use help editing content on the site. Please contact us on [Twitter](https://twitter.com/NSAcodenames) if you would like to become an editor.\n4. Finally, we are still working out the technical part of this project; if you find bugs or you have feature requests, please [report them on GitHub](https://github.com/mehaase/nsa-codenames/issues). We also accept pull requests.\n\nThe entire project is open source, so you are encouraged to look at the source code and you can even set up your own mirror, if you so desire.\n\n## API\n\nThis site features a REST API. The API is not documented (yet!) and it is subject to change, but if you are interested in using this data in your own projects, please take a look at [our source code](https://github.com/mehaase/nsa-codenames). This website itself is an API client; all data is requested via API and the rendering is 100% client-side.','2016-01-04 05:32:54'),(2,'home','## Overview\n\nThis site provide an index of publicly known NSA surveillance tools and programs. *This is not a leak site*. We publish synopses and links to news articles and primary sources, in order to provide readers with a centralized and easy-to-read index.\n\nA graphic is paired with each codename to provide color and illustration for the accompanying text. All graphics are contributed by the community. We encourage you to submit your own! The highest voted graphics will be display most prominently.\n\nFor more information, please read our [about page](/about).\n\n## Featured Codename: [GUNMAN](/gunman)\n\nNot all NSA operations are secret: the agency declassifies some programs many years after they occur. In the case of GUNMAN, the agency declassified the operation 25 years after it completed, providing a rich and colorful historic record for the American public to enjoy.\n\nGUNMAN has all of the key elements of a spy movie: an American embassy, Russian spies, and nerdy NSA engineers working around the clock. The operation is historically important for many reasons, most importantly the way it affected perceptions about the NSA within the U.S. government.','2016-02-04 16:29:25');
